{"title_page": "Expo 2000", "text_new": "{{short description|World exposition in Hanover, Germany in 2000}}\n{{for|the Kraftwerk song|Expo 2000 (song)}}\n{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = \n| class           = Universal\n| category        = \n| image           = EXPO 2000 Hannover Logo.png\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = Expo 2000 logo\n| year            = 2000\n| name            = Expo 2000\n| motto           = \n| building        = Expo 2000 DachHolzkonstruktion\n| area            = {{convert|160|ha|acre|abbr=off}}\n| invent          = \n| visitors        = 18,100,000<ref>https://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/soziales/expo-2000-in-hannover-was-wurde-aus-der-weltausstellung-a-990666.html</ref>\n| organized       = \n| mascot = [[Twipsy]]\n| cnt             = 180\n| org             = 2\n| biz             = \n| country         = Germany\n| city            = [[Hannover]]\n| venue           = [[Kronsberg]]\n| coord           = {{Coord|52|19|18|N|9|48|44|E|format=dms|type:landmark_region:DE}}\n| cand            = 1988\n| award           = {{start date|1990|06|14|df=y}}\n| open            = {{start date|2000|06|1|df=y}} \n| close           = {{start date|2000|10|31|df=y}}\n| prevexpo        = [[Seville Expo '92|Expo '92]]\n| prevcity        = [[Seville]]\n| nextexpo        = [[Expo 2005]]\n| nextcity        = [[Aichi]]\n| suppl           = \n| prevsuppl       = [[Expo '98]] \n| prevsupcity     = [[Lisbon]] \n| nextsuppl       = [[Expo 2008]] \n| nextsupcity     = [[Zaragoza]] \n| prevunho        = [[1999 World Horticultural Exposition|1999 Kunming]] \n| prevunhocity    = [[Kunming]]\n| nextunho        = [[Floriade 2002]]\n| nextunhocity    = [[Haarlemmermeer]]\n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = \n| simhor          = \n| simoth          = \n| website         =  \n}}\n\n[[Image:Pavillon of Hope (Manfred R\u00f6ben).jpg|200px|thumb|German Expo 2000 landmark Pavilion of Hope]]\n[[File:Monaco Pavilion.jpg|thumb|Monaco Pavilion by Architect Hans Ferdinand Degraeuwe]]\n[[Image:Expo2000 nl.jpg|200px|thumb|The Netherlands Pavilion at EXPO 2000]]\n[[Image:Expo2000 venezuela1.jpg|200px|thumb|The Venezuela Pavilion]]\n[[Image:Expo2000Hungary.jpg|200px|thumb|Hungary Pavilion]]\n[[Image:Twipsy2.jpg|200px|thumb|EXPO Mascot '''[[Twipsy]]''']]\n[[File:Hbk braunschweig bibliothek.jpg|thumb|The Mexico pavilion in its new home as the library of the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig|HBK]]]]\n[[File:Expo 2000 and the Skyliner.jpg|thumb|Expo 2000 and the cableway (Skyliner)]]\n\n'''Expo 2000''' was a [[World Expo]] held in [[Hanover]], Germany from Thursday 1 June to Tuesday 31 October 2000. It was located on the [[Hanover Fairground]] (Messegel\u00e4nde Hannover), which is the largest exhibition ground in the world. Initially some 40 million people were expected to attend the exhibition over the course of months, however eventually with less than half of this number the Expo was a flop and turned out a financial failure.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/wirtschaft/expo-flop-die-sponsoren-der-weltausstellung-werden-nervoes/154892.html|title=Expo-Flop: Die Sponsoren der Weltausstellung werden nerv\u00f6s|language=de|author1=Antje Sirleschtov|author2=Imre Grimm|date=21 July 2000|newspaper=Der Tagesspiegel|trans-title=Expo-Flop: The Sponsors of the World Exhibition are getting Nervous}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/revisiting-hanover-10-years-after-expo-2000/a-5510543|title=Revisiting Hanover 10 years after Expo 2000|publisher=Deutsche Welle|author=Hilke Janssen|editor= Rob Mudge|date=28 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite thesis|url=https://honors.libraries.psu.edu/catalog/1697|title=Explicating Failure: Expo 2000|last=Jones|first=Zachary Mark|type=Bachelor of Architecture|date=May 2011|publisher=Penn State University}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2000/05/27/world-class-failure/0c583971-b070-423f-b3f0-c0878f95299d/|title=World-Class Failure|first1=Benjamin|last1=Forgey|first2=Benjamin|last2=Forgey|date=27 May 2000|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20000601&slug=4024011|title=Is German Expo a failure even before it gets started?|author=Carol J. Williams|date=1 June 2000|newspaper=The Seattle Times|via=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nThe Expo's masterplan was designed in a joint venture with Studio d'Arnaboldi / Cavadini, Locarno and AS&P ([[Albert Speer, Jr.|Albert Speer]] und Partner GmbH).\n\n==History==\n\n===Background===\nOn 14 June 1990 the international organization sanctioning World Expos [[Bureau International des Expositions]] awarded Expo 2000 to Hanover, beating out [[Toronto]] by a 21 to 20 vote. In 1992, the architects Studio Arnaboldi/Cavadini of Locarno won an international design competition for the masterplan of the exhibition grounds. On 12 June that year, a survey conducted by the city council was made public showing only 51.5% of area residents supported hosting the expo.\n\n===Construction===\nOn 5 May 1994 a new company was created by the government in Bonn, '''Gesellschaft zur Vorbereitung und Durchf\u00fchrung der Weltausstellung EXPO 2000 in Hannover''' (EXPO 2000 Hannover GmbH). Headed by chairman Helmut Werner, the company was responsible for the construction and management of the Expo.\n\nIn 1995 the supervisory board agreed on the concept for the thematics of the Expo. Construction finally began on 22 April 1996.\n\nUnlike previous expos, which focused on present advances in science and technology, EXPO 2000 focused more on developing and presenting solutions for the future.\n\n===World Expo 2000===\nThe Expo opened to the public on Thursday 1 June 2000 and ran for five months, ending on Tuesday 31 October.\n\nThe Expo site was situated on the original 1,000,000 square meters of the [[Hanover fairground]]; an additional 600,000 m\u00b2 was also made available as a newly opened section to the grounds. As a visitor walked in and tickets were taken, looking above to the approximately four-story-high ceiling, a visitor would have noticed the huge circular pods that held large TVs showing animated people greeting the visitors and providing tourist information in different languages. Some ten large [[McDonald's]] restaurants were also built, along with restaurants representing several of the exhibitor countries. Small retail locations were also set up to supply Expo merchandise. The [[United States]] reversed its decision to take part at a relatively late stage, and the area set aside for the American pavilion was left undeveloped.\n\n40,000,000 visitors were expected at Expo 2000, but only 25,210,000 people came to see the event.  This led to a financial deficit of about $600,000,000.  With pre-ordered tickets priced at 69 DM, the Expo seemed expensive compared to other days out.  Commentator Georg Giersberg wrote in the ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine]]'' that entrance fees for Germany's 53 main theme parks cost on average less than half the price of the Expo (about 30 DM).  Other financial shortfalls came from a lack of corporate sponsorship, since it cost US$4.8 million to be an official product supplier or US$14.5 million to become a world partner.\n\nPart of the failure of the Expo was a lack of clear perception of what to expect at Expo 2000, not helped by a \"cerebral\" advertising campaign that had failed to explain what the Expo was for.  In a 2000 ''[[Time magazine|Time]]'' article, a Berlin-based marketing firm, [[Scholz & Friends]], stated that \"the organizers have failed to convey to the public a clear image of what Expo 2000 is going to be: an entertainment park, a blown-up museum, or a nature reserve.\" <!-- Is this a translation back from a German translation of the original article? It sounds funny to me!--> In the same article, Ralf Strobach, secretary of ''Hanover's Citizens' Initiative for Environment Protection'', said that \"For a long time, companies were unsure if they would be putting money in an eco-show or a showcase for their latest inventions.\" Only after the Expo was open and clearly not meeting expectations was a new advertising campaign created, aimed at the domestic market with British actor [[Peter Ustinov]] and German television star [[Verona Pooth|Verona Feldbusch]] and stressing the fun side of the Expo, under the slogan ''\"Das gibt's nur einmal, es kommt nie wieder\"'' (\"This only happens once, it's never coming back\").\n\nThe German band [[Kraftwerk]] created a [[Vocoder|vocoded]] speech signature theme, \"[[Expo 2000 (song)|Expo 2000]]\", which was also developed into a single of the same name. Later, a remix single \"Expo Remix\" was released. The band was also paid US$190,000 for a five-second jingle, leading Chancellor [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] to state that he \"wouldn't have spent so much money\".\n\n== Settlement ==\nThe western slope of [[Kronsberg]] emerged in the late 1990s in conjunction with the EXPO 2000, established an environmental point of settlement at the Hannover Expo. The district is a result of independent evolutionary history and unique structure often perceived as a separate district.\n\n==Pavilions==\n\n===Themed===\n\n*The 21st Century\n*Planet of Visions\n*Human\n*Knowledge\n*Mobility\n*Communication\n*Energy\n*Health\n*Nutrition\n*Environment\n*Basic Needs\n*Future of Labour\n\n===National===\n{{external links|section|date=April 2016}}\nIn total, 155 nations took part. Some are outlined below:\n\n*{{flagicon|Bhutan}}&nbsp;\u2013 '''The Bhutan Pavilion''' A Buddhist Temple brought from Bhutan to the World Exhibition in Hannover, having been prefabricated in 16,000 construction parts in Bhutan.\n*{{flagicon|Finland}}'''Finland'''&nbsp;\u2013 Titled \"Wind Nest\", the building was created by architects Sarlotta Narjus and Antti-Matti Siikala.  Four-storey twin buildings measuring 50 x 7.5&nbsp;m each were clad in heat-treated thermowood.  The two buildings were connected by bridges, allowing visitors to move amongst the three exhibit halls on the first two stories.  A 15&nbsp;m wide birch forest was also created.\n*{{flagicon|Germany}}'''Germany'''&nbsp;\u2013 Designed by architect Wund Gruppe, the 24,000 m\u00b2 building was the largest nation pavilion at Expo.\n*{{flagicon|Japan}}'''Japan'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Japanese Pavilion was a [[gridshell]] structure made out of recycled paper tubes that created a honeycomb-like building. The German authorities refused to allow a paper-only structure, literally held together at the joints by tape, so a secondary supporting structure made of wood was created to obtain the needed legal approval. Designed by architect [[Shigeru Ban]] along with consultants [[Frei Otto]] (the German architect who created the [[Olympic Stadium (Munich)]] and the German pavilion at [[Expo 67]] in Montreal), [[Buro Happold]] (the British engineering firm which created the [[Millennium Dome]]) and Stefan Polonyi (a structural engineering professor), the building took 3 weeks to assemble and covered an exhibit area of 72&nbsp;m (long) x 35&nbsp;m (wide) x 15.5&nbsp;m (high), pavilion lot size: 5,450 m\u00b2 and building surface area: 3,600 m\u00b2.\n*{{flagicon|Latvia}}'''Latvia'''&nbsp;\u2013 about 300,000 people participated<ref name=\"Latvia\">{{cite web|url=https://zime.center/?r=0&action=zime-category&category=expo2000&language=en-GB|title=ZIME|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> in the \"Zime\" project created by [[Armands Strazds]] and [[Modris Tenisons]].{{cn|date=April 2016}}\n*{{flagicon|Lithuania|1988}}'''Lithuania'''&nbsp;\u2013 The pavilion was designed by Marina and Audrius Bu\u010das, Gintaras Kuginys, Valdas Ozarinskas and Aida \u010ceponyt\u0117. The building was a futuristic glossy yellow. The main attraction was the film \"Flight over Lithuania\".\n*{{flagicon|Mexico}}'''Mexico'''&nbsp;\u2013 The pavilion consisted of five separate buildings linked by ramps, and after the Expo, was relocated to the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig|Braunschweig Fine Arts College]]. The architect was [[Ricardo Legorreta]].\n*{{flagicon|Monaco}}'''Monaco'''&nbsp;\u2013 Monaco contributed at the exhibition by constructing a hypermodern modular prefabricated pavilion which was designed by the architect Hans Ferdinand Degraeuwe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/a/mie.mc/mie/expositions/2000---honnover-germany/monaco-2000 |accessdate=16 November 2011|title=Monaco 2000 - Monaco Inter Expo}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Mongolia}}'''Mongolia'''&nbsp;\u2013Mongolia participated at the exhibition by constructing a nomadic town of the 13th century, called \"[[Chingis]]\u2019s Town\", covering one hectare. The pavilion was designed by the architect Adiya Baldandorj Bayud, to show the [[Yurt|ger]] residences of Great [[Khan (title)|Khans]] of the [[Mongol Empire]] of the 13th century. The feature of this town was that it created the town with ger, ger-carriage and various kinds of cotton residents, which are different in forms, sizes and applications, used by Mongolians of that century. Moreover, the King\u2019s privilege armchair, clothing and accessories of ancient heroes and weapons were shown in the \"Chingis's Town\".http://mongolwall.com/mw_wp/\n*{{flagicon|Netherlands}}'''Netherlands''' was located at '3' Europa Boulevard, and the Dutch pavilion was one of the most popular buildings, winning international acclaim, and was designed by the firm [[MVRDV]]. The theme of the 36&nbsp;m high building (the Expo's tallest structure) was \"Holland creates Space\". Six Holland eco-system landscapes were stacked to showcase how a country can make the most out of a small space. Guests entered on the ground floor and moved through the exhibit space via grand exterior staircases that wrapped around the building. The top level contained a small lake surrounded with windmills that generated power for the building. The interior spaces were designed by MET Studio. The original plan was to dismantle the building and move it back to Amsterdam, but it was determined that it would be much cheaper to just create a new building from scratch. As of 2006, the building sits empty and is partially looted with windows smashed and garbage everywhere. [http://www.ivarhagendoorn.com/photos/architecture/mvrdv_expo2000.html Photos of the building in its current state]; also visit: [http://www.dutchpavilion.nl/ for more updates on the pavilion].\n*{{flagicon|Portugal}}'''Portugal'''&nbsp;\u2013 Designed by architects \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira and Eduardo Souto de Moura, the 2,350 m\u00b2 pavilion was located on the ''Europa Boulevard''. The prefabricated two-story building was covered with around 55 tons of expanded cork agglomerate and with hand-made glazed tiles on the patio and had a double glass fibre canvas membrane roof. [http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20000621015724/http://www.hannover2000.mct.pt/ Portugal Pavilion Website]\n*{{flagicon|Spain}}'''Spain'''&nbsp;\u2013 Designed with the theme \"Familiarity and Solidarity\" [ Spain Pavilion Website]\n*{{flagicon|Switzerland}}'''Switzerland'''&nbsp;\u2013 The 3019 square meter pavilion designed by [[Peter Zumthor]] was built of stacked wooden beams of larchwood and Scots pine held together by steel rods and springs<ref>{{cite book|page= 168|isbn=3-7757-0924-X|author=Hatje Cantz|title=Architektur Architecture EXPO 2000 Hannover}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|UAE}}'''UAE United Arab Emirates'''&nbsp;\u2013 The 3000 m\u00b2 pavilion, situated on a 6000 m\u00b2 plot (the largest of the Expo sites), was a recreated desert fort. Designed by the French architect [[Alain Durand-Heriot]], the exhibit tried to evoke the feeling of being in the Arab state. The main attraction was a 360\u00b0 circular cinema. The building was 84&nbsp;m \u00d7 36&nbsp;m and built out of recyclable materials. The theme of the pavilion was \"From the traditional to the modern\" and presented the history of the country.\n*{{flagicon|Venezuela|1954}}'''Venezuela'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[pavilion]] was a convertible tent structure which opened and closed like a flower. It was very lightweight, was constructed with no waste and completely re-usable. The flower petals were positioned according to the weather, to shade, keep dry or allow sun to shine on the pavilion. It was designed by [[Fruto Vivas]] and [[Frei Otto]] with [[Mahmoud Bodo Rasch|SL Rasch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tensinet.com/database/viewProject/4003|title=Expo 2000 (Hannover): Venezuelan Pavilion|accessdate=5 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130805082055/http://www.tensinet.com/database/viewProject/4003|archive-date=5 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n*'''Planet m \u2013 Media for Mankind'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.bertelsmann.com/en/milestones/view/84 |title=Bertelsmann website|accessdate=2018-04-18}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Bertelsmann]] pavilion, designed by [[TRIAD Berlin]], explored the importance of the media. Guests were brought to the exhibition by the world's largest elevator, which could transport up to 200 people at once. Today, the building is used by the [[Hochschule Hannover|University of Applied Sciences Hannover]].\n*'''BMW World'''&nbsp;\u2013 The exhibit focused on [[BMW]]'s efforts to create clean-energy operated vehicles. The BMW 750hL Clean Energy car was on display. There were also exhibits on the possibilities of solar- and water-fueled cars. Daimler Chrysler also operated '''Lab.01''', an interactive laboratory showcasing mobility devices including mini-robots.\n*'''EU European Union'''&nbsp;\u2013 The pavilion presented the European Union's vision of Europe. The walk-through exhibit was divided into seven zones: 50's, Time Shuttle, Euro, Blue Planet, Bridge, Tunnel, Here and Now. [https://web.archive.org/web/20060506040252/http://europa.eu.int/expo2000/pavilion/index_en.htm Pavilion Webpage]\n*'''Global House'''&nbsp;\u2013 The building housed the '''One World Cafe''' and a variety of exhibits, including '''Indigenous Peoples' Wisdom from the Earth''', a display of 26 initiatives by indigenous groups from around the globe. Each initiative was shown in a flight case and featured text, images, and in many cases, contemporary handicraft. The exhibit was the first opportunity for indigenous people to represent themselves at a World Expo.\n*'''WWF''' ([[World Wildlife Fund]])&nbsp;\u2013 Pavilion\n*'''The ZERI Pavilion'''&nbsp;\u2013 The largest bamboo structure designed by Simon Velez, was built by 41 Colombian wood workers in less than three months. Over 4,500 bamboos (''Guadua angustifolia'') were joined to become the first building which dances with the rhythm of the earth&nbsp;\u2014 and this with a German building permit. Nine months of intensive scientific research and testing first enabled the acquisition of a temporary permit, and after the building was constructed twice (once in Manizales, Colombia and once in Hanover), the final permit was granted the day before the opening of the Expo 2000. This pavilion presented seven projects from around the world which demonstrated that it is possible to respond to everyone's needs on Earth with what we have. The projects from Colombia, Zimbabwe, Fiji, Sweden and Japan inspired many young people. The pavilion nearly went bankrupt when sales and attendance were so low, but thanks to a single bamboo in the center of the pavilion, enough money was collected to make it to the end. The ZERI Pavilion had an estimated 6.4 million visitors, but it had no doors and no queues. [http://www.zeri.org for information on ZERI today]\n*'''Christ Pavilion'''&nbsp;\u2013 Christ Pavilion of the Protestant and Catholic churches in Germany, 2001 reconstructed at the monastery Volkenroda.\n\n==Projects==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050829185121/http://www.lost-paradise-lost.de/ Lost Paradise Lost] - art meets church\n* [http://www.regenwaldhaus.de/ Rain Forest House] - hear, smell, taste and feel the diversity of the tropical highland rain forest\n* [http://www.zoo-hannover.de/ Hannover Zoo] - where the animals can live in conditions similar to their natural habitats\n* [http://www.hornemann-institut.de/index_en.php/ Hornemann Institute] - worldwide knowledge transfer as well as further education in the field of conservation and restoration\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130510103004/http://consumer.discoverohio.com/searchdetails.aspx?detail=66937 Worlds Children Peace Monument (WCPM)] - conceived during EXPO 2000's Culture on the Move segment in cooperation with the United Nations 2000 Culture of Peace Program. The WCPM project, still in use today, encourages positive community participation through the establishment of works of public art, through cultural education and entrepreneurial training to children around the World.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:ARCHIGLASS Tomasz Urbanowicz Zjednoczony \u015awiat Parlament Europejski.jpg|thumb|Glass sculpture \"[[United Earth]]\" by [[Tomasz Urbanowicz]] from EXPO 2000, rebuild in the [[Seat of the European Parliament in Strasbourg|European Parliament in Strasbourg]]. ]]\n[[Image:Nepal Himalaya Pavillon Wiesent 14.jpg|thumb|The Nepal Himalaya Pavilion from the Expo 2000, rebuilt with a small botanical garden at [[Wiesent, Bavaria|Wiesent]] near [[Regensburg]]]]\nSome of the buildings on the Expo site were sold after EXPO 2000 ended, but most of the exhibition area is still used for major fairs in Germany, as it has been since 1949. The southeastern area around [[Expo Plaza]] has been turned into Hanover's new centre of information technology, design, media and arts.\n\nMost of the national pavilion buildings were demolished, or disassembled and shipped to their home countries, following the Expo. Some buildings  were retained, including the Netherlands Pavilion. The structure has now fallen into disrepair, until earlier in December 2017, when architecture company MVRDV announced plans to restore and renovate the Netherlands pavilion to accommodate future users.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nA glass sculpture called \"[[United Earth]]\" by [[Tomasz Urbanowicz]] exhibited as part of the [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Lower Silesian]] Presentation in the Polish Pavillion<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Durczak|first=Miros\u0142aw|date=2000-12-31|title=Region Dolny \u015al\u0105sk nr 8/2000, Wydanie Milenijne|script-title=|trans-title=In Hanover, Lower Silesia at the EXPO 2000|url=http://jbc.jelenia-gora.pl/Content/17508/RDS08_2000.pdf|journal=Region Dolny \u015al\u0105sk|language=pl|publisher=Stowarzyszenie na Rzecz Promocji Dolnego \u015al\u0105ska|volume=8/2000|pages=27-29|issn=1506-29-29|via=Wroc\u0142aw: Stowarzyszenie na Recz Promocji Dolnego \u015al\u0105ska}}</ref> was later handed over by the City of [[Wroc\u0142aw]] to the [[Seat of the European Parliament in Strasbourg|European Parliament in Strasbourg]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wroclaw.wyborcza.pl/wroclaw/1,35771,2700126.html?disableRedirects=true|title=Wyborcza.pl|website=wroclaw.wyborcza.pl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. The sculpture is the main central point of the Agora of the [[Louise Weiss building]] designed by [[Architecture-Studio]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hannover Principles]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Expo 2000}}\n*[http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/2000-hannover Official website of the BIE]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001018012614/http://expo2000.de/home_40_e.html |date=October 18, 2000 |title=www.expo2000.de }}\n*[http://site.expo2000.de/expo2000 Erlebnis Expo 2000] (in German and English)\n*[http://www.luszcz.de/expo2000/index.html Expo 2000, die Weltausstellung in Hannover] (in German and English)\n*[http://www.epo.org/law-practice/legal-texts/official-journal/2016/etc/se4/p219.html European Patent Office]\n*[http://www.expo2000.org/ Exposeeum und Weltausstellungen: Das Museum an der Expo Plaza] (in German)\n*[http://www.studylove.org/worldsfairs29.html#2000 2000 Hannover (BIE World Expo)] - approximately 150 links\n*[http://www.expomuseum.com/2000 Expo2000 at ExpoMuseum.com]\n\n{{List of world exhibitions}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2000 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expo 2000| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|World exposition in Hanover, Germany in 2000}}\n{{for|the Kraftwerk song|Expo 2000 (song)}}\n{{Infobox World's Fair\n| box_width       = \n| class           = Universal\n| category        = \n| image           = EXPO 2000 Hannover Logo.png\n| image_width     = \n| caption         = Expo 2000 logo\n| year            = 2000\n| name            = Expo 2000\n| motto           = \n| building        = Expo 2000 DachHolzkonstruktion\n| area            = {{convert|160|ha|acre|abbr=off}}\n| invent          = \n| visitors        = 18,100,000<ref>https://www.spiegel.de/wirtschaft/soziales/expo-2000-in-hannover-was-wurde-aus-der-weltausstellung-a-990666.html</ref>\n| organized       = \n| mascot = [[Twipsy]]\n| cnt             = 180\n| org             = 2\n| biz             = \n| country         = Germany\n| city            = [[Hannover]]\n| venue           = [[Kronsberg]]\n| coord           = {{Coord|52|19|18|N|9|48|44|E|format=dms|type:landmark_region:DE}}\n| cand            = 1988\n| award           = {{start date|1990|06|14|df=y}}\n| open            = {{start date|2000|06|1|df=y}} \n| close           = {{start date|2000|10|31|df=y}}\n| prevexpo        = [[Seville Expo '92|Expo '92]]\n| prevcity        = [[Seville]]\n| nextexpo        = [[Expo 2005]]\n| nextcity        = [[Aichi]]\n| suppl           = \n| prevsuppl       = [[Expo '98]] \n| prevsupcity     = [[Lisbon]] \n| nextsuppl       = [[Expo 2008]] \n| nextsupcity     = [[Zaragoza]] \n| prevunho        = [[1999 World Horticultural Exposition|1999 Kunming]] \n| prevunhocity    = [[Kunming]]\n| nextunho        = [[Floriade 2002]]\n| nextunhocity    = [[Haarlemmermeer]]\n| simuni          = \n| simspe          = \n| simhor          = \n| simoth          = \n| website         =  \n}}\n\n[[Image:Pavillon of Hope (Manfred R\u00f6ben).jpg|200px|thumb|German Expo 2000 landmark Pavilion of Hope]]\n[[File:Monaco Pavilion.jpg|thumb|Monaco Pavilion by Architect Hans Ferdinand Degraeuwe]]\n[[Image:Expo2000 nl.jpg|200px|thumb|The Netherlands Pavilion at EXPO 2000]]\n[[Image:Expo2000 venezuela1.jpg|200px|thumb|The Venezuela Pavilion]]\n[[Image:Expo2000Hungary.jpg|200px|thumb|Hungary Pavilion]]\n[[Image:Twipsy2.jpg|200px|thumb|EXPO Mascot '''[[Twipsy]]''']]\n[[File:Hbk braunschweig bibliothek.jpg|thumb|The Mexico pavilion in its new home as the library of the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig|HBK]]]]\n[[File:Expo 2000 and the Skyliner.jpg|thumb|Expo 2000 and the cableway (Skyliner)]]\n\n'''Expo 2000''' was a [[World Expo]] held in [[Hanover]], Germany from Thursday 1 June to Tuesday 31 October 2000. It was located on the [[Hanover Fairground]] (Messegel\u00e4nde Hannover), which is the largest exhibition ground in the world. Initially some 40 million people were expected to attend the exhibition over the course of months, however eventually with less than half of this number the Expo was a flop and turned out a financial failure.<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://www.tagesspiegel.de/wirtschaft/expo-flop-die-sponsoren-der-weltausstellung-werden-nervoes/154892.html|title=Expo-Flop: Die Sponsoren der Weltausstellung werden nerv\u00f6s|language=de|author1=Antje Sirleschtov|author2=Imre Grimm|date=21 July 2000|newspaper=Der Tagesspiegel|trans-title=Expo-Flop: The Sponsors of the World Exhibition are getting Nervous}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.com/en/revisiting-hanover-10-years-after-expo-2000/a-5510543|title=Revisiting Hanover 10 years after Expo 2000|publisher=Deutsche Welle|author=Hilke Janssen|editor= Rob Mudge|date=28 April 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite thesis|url=https://honors.libraries.psu.edu/catalog/1697|title=Explicating Failure: Expo 2000|last=Jones|first=Zachary Mark|type=Bachelor of Architecture|date=May 2011|publisher=Penn State University}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/2000/05/27/world-class-failure/0c583971-b070-423f-b3f0-c0878f95299d/|title=World-Class Failure|first1=Benjamin|last1=Forgey|first2=Benjamin|last2=Forgey|date=27 May 2000|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20000601&slug=4024011|title=Is German Expo a failure even before it gets started?|author=Carol J. Williams|date=1 June 2000|newspaper=The Seattle Times|via=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nThe Expo's masterplan was designed in a joint venture with Studio d'Arnaboldi / Cavadini, Locarno and AS&P ([[Albert Speer, Jr.|Albert Speer]] und Partner GmbH).\n\n==History==\n\n===Background===\nOn 14 June 1990 the international organization sanctioning World Expos [[Bureau International des Expositions]] awarded Expo 2000 to Hanover, beating out [[Toronto]] by a 21 to 20 vote. In 1992, the architects Studio Arnaboldi/Cavadini of Locarno won an international design competition for the masterplan of the exhibition grounds. On 12 June that year, a survey conducted by the city council was made public showing only 51.5% of area residents supported hosting the expo.\n\n===Construction===\nOn 5 May 1994 a new company was created by the government in Bonn, '''Gesellschaft zur Vorbereitung und Durchf\u00fchrung der Weltausstellung EXPO 2000 in Hannover''' (EXPO 2000 Hannover GmbH). Headed by chairman Helmut Werner, the company was responsible for the construction and management of the Expo.\n\nIn 1995 the supervisory board agreed on the concept for the thematics of the Expo. Construction finally began on 22 April 1996.\n\nUnlike previous expos, which focused on present advances in science and technology, EXPO 2000 focused more on developing and presenting solutions for the future.\n\n===World Expo 2000===\nThe Expo opened to the public on Thursday 1 June 2000 and ran for five months, ending on Tuesday 31 October.\n\nThe Expo site was situated on the original 1,000,000 square meters of the [[Hanover fairground]]; an additional 600,000 m\u00b2 was also made available as a newly opened section to the grounds. As a visitor walked in and tickets were taken, looking above to the approximately four-story-high ceiling, a visitor would have noticed the huge circular pods that held large TVs showing animated people greeting the visitors and providing tourist information in different languages. Some ten large [[McDonald's]] restaurants were also built, along with restaurants representing several of the exhibitor countries. Small retail locations were also set up to supply Expo merchandise. The [[United States]] reversed its decision to take part at a relatively late stage, and the area set aside for the American pavilion was left undeveloped.\n\n40,000,000 visitors were expected at Expo 2000, but only 25,210,000 people came to see the event.  This led to a financial deficit of about $600,000,000.  With pre-ordered tickets priced at 69 DM, the Expo seemed expensive compared to other days out.  Commentator Georg Giersberg wrote in the ''[[Frankfurter Allgemeine]]'' that entrance fees for Germany's 53 main theme parks cost on average less than half the price of the Expo (about 30 DM).  Other financial shortfalls came from a lack of corporate sponsorship, since it cost US$4.8 million to be an official product supplier or US$14.5 million to become a world partner.\n\nPart of the failure of the Expo was a lack of clear perception of what to expect at Expo 2000, not helped by a \"cerebral\" advertising campaign that had failed to explain what the Expo was for.  In a 2000 ''[[Time magazine|Time]]'' article, a Berlin-based marketing firm, [[Scholz & Friends]], stated that \"the organizers have failed to convey to the public a clear image of what Expo 2000 is going to be: an entertainment park, a blown-up museum, or a nature reserve.\" <!-- Is this a translation back from a German translation of the original article? It sounds funny to me!--> In the same article, Ralf Strobach, secretary of ''Hanover's Citizens' Initiative for Environment Protection'', said that \"For a long time, companies were unsure if they would be putting money in an eco-show or a showcase for their latest inventions.\" Only after the Expo was open and clearly not meeting expectations was a new advertising campaign created, aimed at the domestic market with British actor [[Peter Ustinov]] and German television star [[Verona Pooth|Verona Feldbusch]] and stressing the fun side of the Expo, under the slogan ''\"Das gibt's nur einmal, es kommt nie wieder\"'' (\"This only happens once, it's never coming back\").\n\nThe German band [[Kraftwerk]] created a [[Vocoder|vocoded]] speech signature theme, \"[[Expo 2000 (song)|Expo 2000]]\", which was also developed into a single of the same name. Later, a remix single \"Expo Remix\" was released. The band was also paid US$190,000 for a five-second jingle, leading Chancellor [[Gerhard Schr\u00f6der]] to state that he \"wouldn't have spent so much money\".\n\n== Settlement ==\nThe western slope of [[Kronsberg]] emerged in the late 1990s in conjunction with the EXPO 2000, established an environmental point of settlement at the Hannover Expo. The district is a result of independent evolutionary history and unique structure often perceived as a separate district.\n\n==Pavilions==\n\n===Themed===\n\n*The 21st Century\n*Planet of Visions\n*Human\n*Knowledge\n*Mobility\n*Communication\n*Energy\n*Health\n*Nutrition\n*Environment\n*Basic Needs\n*Future of Labour\n\n===National===\n{{external links|section|date=April 2016}}\nIn total, 155 nations took part. Some are outlined below:\n\n*{{flagicon|Bhutan}}&nbsp;\u2013 '''The Bhutan Pavilion''' A Buddhist Temple brought from Bhutan to the World Exhibition in Hannover, having been prefabricated in 16,000 construction parts in Bhutan.\n*{{flagicon|Finland}}'''Finland'''&nbsp;\u2013 Titled \"Wind Nest\", the building was created by architects Sarlotta Narjus and Antti-Matti Siikala.  Four-storey twin buildings measuring 50 x 7.5&nbsp;m each were clad in heat-treated thermowood.  The two buildings were connected by bridges, allowing visitors to move amongst the three exhibit halls on the first two stories.  A 15&nbsp;m wide birch forest was also created.\n*{{flagicon|Germany}}'''Germany'''&nbsp;\u2013 Designed by architect Wund Gruppe, the 24,000 m\u00b2 building was the largest nation pavilion at Expo.\n*{{flagicon|Japan}}'''Japan'''&nbsp;\u2013 The Japanese Pavilion was a [[gridshell]] structure made out of recycled paper tubes that created a honeycomb-like building. The German authorities refused to allow a paper-only structure, literally held together at the joints by tape, so a secondary supporting structure made of wood was created to obtain the needed legal approval. Designed by architect [[Shigeru Ban]] along with consultants [[Frei Otto]] (the German architect who created the [[Olympic Stadium (Munich)]] and the German pavilion at [[Expo 67]] in Montreal), [[Buro Happold]] (the British engineering firm which created the [[Millennium Dome]]) and Stefan Polonyi (a structural engineering professor), the building took 3 weeks to assemble and covered an exhibit area of 72&nbsp;m (long) x 35&nbsp;m (wide) x 15.5&nbsp;m (high), pavilion lot size: 5,450 m\u00b2 and building surface area: 3,600 m\u00b2.\n*{{flagicon|Latvia}}'''Latvia'''&nbsp;\u2013 about 300,000 people participated<ref name=\"Latvia\">{{cite web|url=https://zime.center/?r=0&action=zime-category&category=expo2000&language=en-GB|title=ZIME|accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> in the \"Zime\" project created by [[Armands Strazds]] and [[Modris Tenisons]].{{cn|date=April 2016}}\n*{{flagicon|Lithuania|1988}}'''Lithuania'''&nbsp;\u2013 The pavilion was designed by Marina and Audrius Bu\u010das, Gintaras Kuginys, Valdas Ozarinskas and Aida \u010ceponyt\u0117. The building was a futuristic glossy yellow. The main attraction was the film \"Flight over Lithuania\".\n*{{flagicon|Mexico}}'''Mexico'''&nbsp;\u2013 The pavilion consisted of five separate buildings linked by ramps, and after the Expo, was relocated to the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Bildende K\u00fcnste Braunschweig|Braunschweig Fine Arts College]]. The architect was [[Ricardo Legorreta]].\n*{{flagicon|Monaco}}'''Monaco'''&nbsp;\u2013 Monaco contributed at the exhibition by constructing a hypermodern modular prefabricated pavilion which was designed by the architect Hans Ferdinand Degraeuwe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sites.google.com/a/mie.mc/mie/expositions/2000---honnover-germany/monaco-2000 |accessdate=16 November 2011|title=Monaco 2000 - Monaco Inter Expo}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|Mongolia}}'''Mongolia'''&nbsp;\u2013Mongolia participated at the exhibition by constructing a nomadic town of the 13th century, called \"[[Chingis]]\u2019s Town\", covering one hectare. The pavilion was designed by the architect Adiya Baldandorj Bayud, to show the [[Yurt|ger]] residences of Great [[Khan (title)|Khans]] of the [[Mongol Empire]] of the 13th century. The feature of this town was that it created the town with ger, ger-carriage and various kinds of cotton residents, which are different in forms, sizes and applications, used by Mongolians of that century. Moreover, the King\u2019s privilege armchair, clothing and accessories of ancient heroes and weapons were shown in the \"Chingis's Town\".http://mongolwall.com/mw_wp/\n*{{flagicon|Netherlands}}'''Netherlands''' was located at '3' Europa Boulevard, and the Dutch pavilion was one of the most popular buildings, winning international acclaim, and was designed by the firm [[MVRDV]]. The theme of the 36&nbsp;m high building (the Expo's tallest structure) was \"Holland creates Space\". Six Holland eco-system landscapes were stacked to showcase how a country can make the most out of a small space. Guests entered on the ground floor and moved through the exhibit space via grand exterior staircases that wrapped around the building. The top level contained a small lake surrounded with windmills that generated power for the building. The interior spaces were designed by MET Studio. The original plan was to dismantle the building and move it back to Amsterdam, but it was determined that it would be much cheaper to just create a new building from scratch. As of 2006, the building sits empty and is partially looted with windows smashed and garbage everywhere. [http://www.ivarhagendoorn.com/photos/architecture/mvrdv_expo2000.html Photos of the building in its current state]; also visit: [http://www.dutchpavilion.nl/ for more updates on the pavilion].\n*{{flagicon|Portugal}}'''Portugal'''&nbsp;\u2013 Designed by architects \u00c1lvaro Siza Vieira and Eduardo Souto de Moura, the 2,350 m\u00b2 pavilion was located on the ''Europa Boulevard''. The prefabricated two-story building was covered with around 55 tons of expanded cork agglomerate and with hand-made glazed tiles on the patio and had a double glass fibre canvas membrane roof. [http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20000621015724/http://www.hannover2000.mct.pt/ Portugal Pavilion Website]\n*{{flagicon|Spain}}'''Spain'''&nbsp;\u2013 Designed with the theme \"Familiarity and Solidarity\" [ Spain Pavilion Website]\n*{{flagicon|Switzerland}}'''Switzerland'''&nbsp;\u2013 The 3019 square meter pavilion designed by [[Peter Zumthor]] was built of stacked wooden beams of larchwood and Scots pine held together by steel rods and springs<ref>{{cite book|page= 168|isbn=3-7757-0924-X|author=Hatje Cantz|title=Architektur Architecture EXPO 2000 Hannover}}</ref>\n*{{flagicon|UAE}}'''UAE United Arab Emirates'''&nbsp;\u2013 The 3000 m\u00b2 pavilion, situated on a 6000 m\u00b2 plot (the largest of the Expo sites), was a recreated desert fort. Designed by the French architect [[Alain Durand-Heriot]], the exhibit tried to evoke the feeling of being in the Arab state. The main attraction was a 360\u00b0 circular cinema. The building was 84&nbsp;m \u00d7 36&nbsp;m and built out of recyclable materials. The theme of the pavilion was \"From the traditional to the modern\" and presented the history of the country.\n*{{flagicon|Venezuela|1954}}'''Venezuela'''&nbsp;\u2013 The [[pavilion]] was a convertible tent structure which opened and closed like a flower. It was very lightweight, was constructed with no waste and completely re-usable. The flower petals were positioned according to the weather, to shade, keep dry or allow sun to shine on the pavilion. It was designed by [[Fruto Vivas]] and [[Frei Otto]] with [[Mahmoud Bodo Rasch|SL Rasch]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tensinet.com/database/viewProject/4003|title=Expo 2000 (Hannover): Venezuelan Pavilion|accessdate=5 June 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130805082055/http://www.tensinet.com/database/viewProject/4003|archive-date=5 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Other===\n*'''Planet m \u2013 Media for Mankind'''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://history.bertelsmann.com/en/milestones/view/84 |title=Bertelsmann website|accessdate=2018-04-18}}</ref>&nbsp;\u2013 The [[Bertelsmann]] pavilion, designed by [[TRIAD Berlin]], explored the importance of the media. Guests were brought to the exhibition by the world's largest elevator, which could transport up to 200 people at once. Today, the building is used by the [[Hochschule Hannover|University of Applied Sciences Hannover]].\n*'''BMW World'''&nbsp;\u2013 The exhibit focused on [[BMW]]'s efforts to create clean-energy operated vehicles. The BMW 750hL Clean Energy car was on display. There were also exhibits on the possibilities of solar- and water-fueled cars. Daimler Chrysler also operated '''Lab.01''', an interactive laboratory showcasing mobility devices including mini-robots.\n*'''EU European Union'''&nbsp;\u2013 The pavilion presented the European Union's vision of Europe. The walk-through exhibit was divided into seven zones: 50's, Time Shuttle, Euro, Blue Planet, Bridge, Tunnel, Here and Now. [https://web.archive.org/web/20060506040252/http://europa.eu.int/expo2000/pavilion/index_en.htm Pavilion Webpage]\n*'''Global House'''&nbsp;\u2013 The building housed the '''One World Cafe''' and a variety of exhibits, including '''Indigenous Peoples' Wisdom from the Earth''', a display of 26 initiatives by indigenous groups from around the globe. Each initiative was shown in a flight case and featured text, images, and in many cases, contemporary handicraft. The exhibit was the first opportunity for indigenous people to represent themselves at a World Expo.\n*'''WWF''' ([[World Wildlife Fund]])&nbsp;\u2013 Pavilion\n*'''The ZERI Pavilion'''&nbsp;\u2013 The largest bamboo structure designed by Simon Velez, was built by 41 Colombian wood workers in less than three months. Over 4,500 bamboos (''Guadua angustifolia'') were joined to become the first building which dances with the rhythm of the earth&nbsp;\u2014 and this with a German building permit. Nine months of intensive scientific research and testing first enabled the acquisition of a temporary permit, and after the building was constructed twice (once in Manizales, Colombia and once in Hanover), the final permit was granted the day before the opening of the Expo 2000. This pavilion presented seven projects from around the world which demonstrated that it is possible to respond to everyone's needs on Earth with what we have. The projects from Colombia, Zimbabwe, Fiji, Sweden and Japan inspired many young people. The pavilion nearly went bankrupt when sales and attendance were so low, but thanks to a single bamboo in the center of the pavilion, enough money was collected to make it to the end. The ZERI Pavilion had an estimated 6.4 million visitors, but it had no doors and no queues. [http://www.zeri.org for information on ZERI today]\n*'''Christ Pavilion'''&nbsp;\u2013 Christ Pavilion of the Protestant and Catholic churches in Germany, 2001 reconstructed at the monastery Volkenroda.\n\n==Projects==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050829185121/http://www.lost-paradise-lost.de/ Lost Paradise Lost] - art meets church\n* [http://www.regenwaldhaus.de/ Rain Forest House] - hear, smell, taste and feel the diversity of the tropical highland rain forest\n* [http://www.zoo-hannover.de/ Hannover Zoo] - where the animals can live in conditions similar to their natural habitats\n* [http://www.hornemann-institut.de/index_en.php/ Hornemann Institute] - worldwide knowledge transfer as well as further education in the field of conservation and restoration\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20130510103004/http://consumer.discoverohio.com/searchdetails.aspx?detail=66937 Worlds Children Peace Monument (WCPM)] - conceived during EXPO 2000's Culture on the Move segment in cooperation with the United Nations 2000 Culture of Peace Program. The WCPM project, still in use today, encourages positive community participation through the establishment of works of public art, through cultural education and entrepreneurial training to children around the World.\n\n==Legacy==\n[[File:ARCHIGLASS Tomasz Urbanowicz Zjednoczony \u015awiat Parlament Europejski.jpg|thumb|Glass sculpture \"United Earth\" by [[Tomasz Urbanowicz]] from EXPO 2000, rebuild in the [[Seat of the European Parliament in Strasbourg|European Parliament in Strasbourg]]. ]]\n[[Image:Nepal Himalaya Pavillon Wiesent 14.jpg|thumb|The Nepal Himalaya Pavilion from the Expo 2000, rebuilt with a small botanical garden at [[Wiesent, Bavaria|Wiesent]] near [[Regensburg]]]]\nSome of the buildings on the Expo site were sold after EXPO 2000 ended, but most of the exhibition area is still used for major fairs in Germany, as it has been since 1949. The southeastern area around [[Expo Plaza]] has been turned into Hanover's new centre of information technology, design, media and arts.\n\nMost of the national pavilion buildings were demolished, or disassembled and shipped to their home countries, following the Expo. Some buildings  were retained, including the Netherlands Pavilion. The structure has now fallen into disrepair, until earlier in December 2017, when architecture company MVRDV announced plans to restore and renovate the Netherlands pavilion to accommodate future users.{{Citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nA glass sculpture called \"United Earth\" by [[Tomasz Urbanowicz]] exhibited as part of the [[Lower Silesian Voivodeship|Lower Silesian]] Presentation in the Polish Pavillion<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Durczak|first=Miros\u0142aw|date=2000-12-31|title=Region Dolny \u015al\u0105sk nr 8/2000, Wydanie Milenijne|script-title=|trans-title=In Hanover, Lower Silesia at the EXPO 2000|url=http://jbc.jelenia-gora.pl/Content/17508/RDS08_2000.pdf|journal=Region Dolny \u015al\u0105sk|language=pl|publisher=Stowarzyszenie na Rzecz Promocji Dolnego \u015al\u0105ska|volume=8/2000|pages=27-29|issn=1506-29-29|via=Wroc\u0142aw: Stowarzyszenie na Recz Promocji Dolnego \u015al\u0105ska}}</ref> was later handed over by the City of [[Wroc\u0142aw]] to the [[Seat of the European Parliament in Strasbourg|European Parliament in Strasbourg]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wroclaw.wyborcza.pl/wroclaw/1,35771,2700126.html?disableRedirects=true|title=Wyborcza.pl|website=wroclaw.wyborcza.pl|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>. The sculpture is the main central point of the Agora of the [[Louise Weiss building]] designed by [[Architecture-Studio]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Hannover Principles]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Expo 2000}}\n*[http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/2000-hannover Official website of the BIE]\n*{{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20001018012614/http://expo2000.de/home_40_e.html |date=October 18, 2000 |title=www.expo2000.de }}\n*[http://site.expo2000.de/expo2000 Erlebnis Expo 2000] (in German and English)\n*[http://www.luszcz.de/expo2000/index.html Expo 2000, die Weltausstellung in Hannover] (in German and English)\n*[http://www.epo.org/law-practice/legal-texts/official-journal/2016/etc/se4/p219.html European Patent Office]\n*[http://www.expo2000.org/ Exposeeum und Weltausstellungen: Das Museum an der Expo Plaza] (in German)\n*[http://www.studylove.org/worldsfairs29.html#2000 2000 Hannover (BIE World Expo)] - approximately 150 links\n*[http://www.expomuseum.com/2000 Expo2000 at ExpoMuseum.com]\n\n{{List of world exhibitions}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2000 in Germany]]\n[[Category:Expo 2000| ]]\n", "name_user": "Korek Edit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added wiki-link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expo_2000"}
{"title_page": "Slaughterhouse (group)", "text_new": "{{for|the '90s metal band|Slaughter House (band)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Slaughterhouse\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| years_active     = 2008\u20132018, 2019-present\n| label            = [[Shady Records|Shady]], [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Eminem]]<br/>[[Ludacris]]\n| website          = {{URL|slaughterhouseweb.com}}\n| current_members  = [[Joell Ortiz]]<br />[[Kxng Crooked]]<br />[[Royce da 5'9\"]]|<nowiki>past_members = Joe Budden }}</nowiki>\n| past_members     = [[Joe Budden]]\n}}\n'''Slaughterhouse''' is a [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] consisting of rappers [[Joe Budden]], [[Joell Ortiz]], [[Kxng Crooked]] and [[Royce da 5'9\"]]. They have released two [[studio albums]] as a group, the independent ''[[Slaughterhouse (Slaughterhouse album)|Slaughterhouse]]'' and the [[Shady Records]]/[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]-backed ''[[Welcome to: Our House]]''.\n\n==History==\n\n===2008: Formation===\nThe group formed in late 2008 after Crooked I, Joell Ortiz, Royce da 5'9\", and Joe Budden appeared on the song \"Slaughterhouse\" from Joe Budden's album ''[[Halfway House (album)|Halfway House]]''. They decided to form a group and named the group after the song. The members of Slaughterhouse all share some degree of controversy from their past in the music industry. All four address these issues in the song \"Move On\".\n\n===2009\u20132010: Debut album===\nTheir self-titled debut album was released on August 11, 2009. The album was recorded over a six-day period in early June. The album features production from Focus,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebossboard.com/article.php?newid=176 |title=Slaughterhouse Confirms The E1 Deal |publisher=The B.O.S.S. Board |accessdate=2011-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HIQT0MeD?url=http://www.thebossboard.com/article.php?newid=176 |archivedate=2013-06-11 }}</ref> [[The Alchemist (producer)|The Alchemist]], [[DJ Khalil]], StreetRunner and [[Mr. Porter]] of [[D12]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Koroma |first=Salima |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9213 |title=More Details Emerge About Slaughterhouse Debut &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-05-28 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> On June 18, 2009, the first street single off the album was released via Joe Budden's Twitter account. The track was \"Woodstock (Hood Hop)\" and features [[M.O.P.]] on the hook.<ref name=\"Rock The Bells Tour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.welivethis.com/newsfeed/2009/06/25/slaughterhouse-featuring-mop-hood-hop-woodstock-cdq/ |title=Slaughterhouse - Rock The Bells Tour Dates and Release of Hood Hop |work=WeLiveThis.com |accessdate=June 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703060118/http://www.welivethis.com/newsfeed/2009/06/25/slaughterhouse-featuring-mop-hood-hop-woodstock-cdq/ |archivedate=July 3, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://yaheardhiphop.blogspot.com/2009/06/first-leak-off-slaughterhouses-debut.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090713091753/http://yaheardhiphop.blogspot.com/2009/06/first-leak-off-slaughterhouses-debut.html|date=July 13, 2009}}</ref> The first official single from the album was \"[[The One (Slaughterhouse song)|The One]]\". A second video for the song ''Microphone'' was also released in late 2009. A video directed by [[Rik Cordero]].\n\nTheir debut album sold 18,000 copies in its first week (Only 20,000 copies were shipped to stores).<ref>{{cite web|last=Paine |first=Jake |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9660 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 8/16/2009 &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-08-19 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> As of September 5, 2009 the album has sold 31,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs |first=Allen |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9774 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 9/5/2009 &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-09-09 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref>\n\nThe group initially planned for their second album to release in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|last=Vasquez |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9621 |title=Slaughterhouse Talk Second Album And 2010 Plans &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-08-12 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> tentatively named by Crooked I as ''No Muzzle''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/stories/features/archive/2009/10/28/22000800.aspx |title=Features : Crooked I: Slaughterhouse Superman |publisher=Allhiphop.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> In late 2009, however, [[Royce da 5'9\"]] confirmed talks between the group and [[Shady Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/slaughterhouse/092909-royce-da-59-confirms-that-his-slaughterhouse-group-is-in-talks-with-eminem-and-shady-records.html |title=Royce Confirms Negotiations With Shady Records &#124; Slaughterhouse |publisher=Rap Basement |date=2009-09-29 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Shaheem |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1622494/20090928/eminem.jhtml |title=Are Slaughterhouse Joining Eminem's Shady Records? 'It Would Be A Great Thing,' Royce Da 5'9\" Says - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=2009-09-28 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> stating that he felt their second album should be released on a major label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/royce-59/112709-royce-da-5-9-talks-about-slaughterhouse-future-and-plans-to-sign-with-a-major-label-watch-her.html |title=Royce Talks Slaughterhouse's Future &#124; Royce 59 |publisher=Rap Basement |date=2009-11-27 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132012: Shady Records and ''Welcome to: Our House''===\nAs rumors of a [[Shady Records]]/Slaughterhouse signing spread, in March 2010, Joell Ortiz posted a rant on Twitter denigrating E1 Entertainment for blocking Shady negotiations, implying that another party was involved as well. Responding to a disgruntled Amalgam Digital executive's allegations against him, Joe Budden confirmed that complications regarding E1 and Amalgam were the reason the deal had not been completed previously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musiconplay.net/25/03/2010/joe-budden-responds-to-amalgam-explains-slaughterhouseshady-delay/ |title=Joe Budden Responds To Amalgam, Explains Slaughterhouse/Shady Delay &#124; Music On Play - We The Best FOREVER |publisher=Music On Play |date= |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> Royce da 5'9\" would later name-drop Shady Records in a ''Bar Exam 3'' freestyle,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2010/03/31/royce-da-59-hints-at-slaughterhouseshady-records-deal/ |title=Royce Da 5'9 Hints At Slaughterhouse/Shady Records Deal |publisher=Ballerstatus |date=2010-03-31 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> and the group released a song entitled \"Beamer, Benz or Bentley (ShadyMegaMix)\", while still with E1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=77089 |title=Slaughterhouse \"Beamer, Benz or Bentley (Shady Megamix)\" |website=XXLmag.com |accessdate=April 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424193046/http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=77089 |archivedate=April 24, 2010 }}</ref> Slaughterhouse, minus Joe Budden, were featured on the iTunes deluxe edition of Eminem's [[Recovery (Eminem album)|Recovery]] album on the track \"Session One\", while also still with E1. The group also featured in \"Loud Noises\" on ''[[Hell: The Sequel]]'', a collaborative EP between Royce and Eminem.\n\nPlans to release an EP were revealed by HipHopDX in their Rap Release Dates update in June 2010, tentatively titled ''[[Slaughterhouse EP]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hanna |first=Mitchell |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11540 |title=Wednesday Rap Release Dates: Schoolly D, Curren$y, Bun B &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2010-06-23 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> The EP was released on February 8, 2011, with four new tracks and two remixes by Frequency of tracks previously released. On January 12, 2011, it was confirmed that the group officially signed to [[Shady Records]] along with [[Yelawolf]]. Both acts appeared along with [[Eminem]] on the cover of ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' magazine's March 2011 edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapradar.com/2011/01/12/eminem-covers-xxl-signs-slaughterhouse-yelawolf/ |title=Eminem Covers XXL; Signs Slaughterhouse & Yelawolf |publisher=Rap Radar |date=2011-01-12 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref>\n\nA year later, the group was featured on the cover of the July/August issue of ''The Source'' magazine in anticipation of their Shady Records debut.<ref>{{cite web|last=Osorio |first=Kim |url=http://thesource.com/2012/06/19/slaughterhouseandbeastieboyscoverthenewissueofthesource/ |title=Slaughterhouse and Beastie Boys Cover The New Issue Of The Source |publisher=The Source |date=2012-06-19}}</ref> On July 7, 2012, Royce announced in an interview with Jenny Boom Boom that the group will release a pre-album mixtape around the first week of August. A new single \"Throw It Away\" produced by Swizz Beats, will be off the album \"Welcome to: Our House\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W6ahjiy6ZRI&feature=player_embedded|title=Jenny Boom Boom Interviews Slaughterhouse @ BET Awards 12|publisher=Jenny Boom Boom |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> Joe Budden revealed via Twitter that the mixtape is called \"On The House\" and will be hosted by DJ Drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoeBudden/status/229020898190041088 |title=Twitter / JoeBudden: Real shit tho, the verses on |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> A promotional video for the mixtape was released on August 6, 2012 and previewed a song called \"See Dead People\", with confirmed guest appearances on the mixtape by [[Eminem]] and [[Black Hippy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebossboard.com/article.php?newid=1189 |title=Slaughterhouse Officially Announces Mixtape |publisher=The B.O.S.S. Board |date= |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> On August 16, Slaughterhouse released a new track, \"Truth or Truth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zPBCA41wGHw |title=Slaughterhouse - Truth Or Truth (On The House) |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-08-16 |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> The Mixtape ''[[On the House (album)|On the House]]'' was released on Aug.19th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/Slaughterhouse-On-The-House-mixtape.381972.html |title=Slaughterhouse - On The House Hosted by DJ Drama // Free Mixtape @ |publisher=Datpiff.com |date=2012-08-19 |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> Slaughterhouse released their second studio album ''[[Welcome to: Our House]]'', the first to be released under Shady Records, on August 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18435|title=Slaughterhouse Announces Shady Records Debut ''Welcome to: Our House,''  Tour Dates|publisher=HipHopDX |accessdate=2012-01-26}}</ref> As of November 23, 2012, it has sold 146,000 copies in the US. Budden has admitted to the group abusing substances during the recording of the album however saying the whole group is sober and ready for their third album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22273/title.joe-budden-excited-to-work-on-slaughterhouses-next-album-while-sober/|title=Joe Budden Excited To Work On Slaughterhouse's Next Album While Sober|author=HipHopDX|date=19 December 2012|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013-2018: ''Glass House'' and split ===\nIn May 2013, Slaughterhouse confirmed that they had put their solo projects on hold, and had begun recording for their third studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/05/slaughterhouse-getting-started-with-the-recording-process-for-new-album/ |title=Slaughterhouse \u201cGetting Started With The Recording Process\u201d For New Album - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref> The album will be executive produced by [[Just Blaze]] and contains production by [[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]], [[Cardiak]], [[Illmind]], [[AraabMuzik]] and [[DJ Premier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23466/title.just-blaze-said-to-executive-produce-slaughterhouse-s-third-album-|title=Just Blaze Said To Executive Produce Slaughterhouse's Third Album|author=HipHopDX|date=18 June 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/07/joell-ortiz-the-object-is-to-make-slaughterhouse-one-person/ |title=Joell Ortiz: \u201cThe Object Is To Make Slaughterhouse One Person\u201d - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref> In November 2013, Joe Budden confirmed that the album would be released in early 2014. At the time he also stated that [[Action Bronson]] would be featured on the album, and they had yet to work with Eminem on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26219/title.joe-budden-discusses-slaughterhouse-s-upcoming-album-action-bronson-collaboration|title=Joe Budden Discusses Slaughterhouse's Upcoming Album & Action Bronson Collaboration|author=HipHopDX|date=12 November 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> On May 21, 2014, the group released their second mixtape titled ''[[House Rules (mixtape)|House Rules]]'', which featured 10 tracks with production from [[Nottz]], [[AraabMuzik]], [[DJ Pain 1]], [[The Heatmakerz]], [[Illmind]], [[Harry Fraud]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/houserules|title=Slaughterhouse - House Rules|work=DatPiff|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> On February 19, 2015, Royce Da 5'9\" had confirmed that the album was \"pretty close to being done\", and that the group, along with Eminem were \"nitpicking at it\". He had hoped for a summer release date for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/detroit/index.ssf/2015/02/detroits_royce_da_59_says_slau.html|title=Detroit's Royce da 5'9\" says Slaughterhouse's 'Glass House' album is 'pretty close to being done'|author=Eric Stacy|date=February 19, 2015|accessdate=May 18, 2015}}</ref> On February 7, 2017, Joe Budden confirmed on his podcast that the album will never be released<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/02/joe-budden-new-slaughterhouse-album-never-coming-out/ |title=Joe Budden Says Album Slaughterhouse Recorded Years Ago Is Never Coming Out - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Kxng Crooked announced via Instagram his departure from Slaughterhouse and confirmed that ''Glass House'' \"exists\" but without a release date. He said there were no harsh feelings about his departure: it was \"all love\". Joell Ortiz and Royce da 5'9\" commented on the announcement with respect and support. On April 26, 2018, Royce da 5\u20199\u201d announced that the supergroup had officially disbanded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopwired.com/750854/royce-da-59-confirms-that-slaughterhouse-is-done/|title=Royce Da 5\u20199\u2033 Confirms That Slaughterhouse is \u201cDone\u201d}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Eminem released a four-part interview with SWAY on his YouTube channel explaining the reasons why the group had a downfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wrpauWGy4tQ|title=Eminem x Sway - The Kamikaze Interview (Part 2)|date=September 12, 2018|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the group (minus Joe Budden)  was featured on [[Eminem]]'s eleventh studio album [[Music to Be Murdered By|Music to be Murdered By]] on the track \"I Will\".<ref>https://genius.com/Eminem-i-will-lyrics</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Slaughterhouse discography}}\n\n* ''[[Slaughterhouse (Slaughterhouse album)|Slaughterhouse]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Welcome to: Our House]]'' (2012)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Slaughterhouse}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Slaughterhouse members templates\n|list1=\n{{Crooked I}}\n{{Joe Budden}}\n{{Joell Ortiz}}\n{{Royce da 5'9\"}}\n}}\n{{Shady Records}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slaughterhouse (group)}}\n[[Category:Hip hop supergroups]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Shady Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2018]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the '90s metal band|Slaughter House (band)}}\n{{pp-pc1|small=yes}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Slaughterhouse\n| background       = group_or_band\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| years_active     = 2008\u20132018, 2019-present\n| label            = [[Shady Records|Shady]], [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n| associated_acts  = [[Eminem]]\n| website          = {{URL|slaughterhouseweb.com}}\n| current_members  = [[Joell Ortiz]]<br />[[Kxng Crooked]]<br />[[Royce da 5'9\"]]\n|<nowiki>past_members = Joe Budden }}</nowiki>\n| past_members     = [[Joe Budden]]\n}}\n'''Slaughterhouse''' is a [[Hip hop music|hip hop]] [[supergroup (music)|supergroup]] consisting of rappers [[Joe Budden]], [[Joell Ortiz]], [[Kxng Crooked]] and [[Royce da 5'9\"]]. They have released two [[studio albums]] as a group, the independent ''[[Slaughterhouse (Slaughterhouse album)|Slaughterhouse]]'' and the [[Shady Records]]/[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]-backed ''[[Welcome to: Our House]]''.\n\n==History==\n\n===2008: Formation===\nThe group formed in late 2008 after Crooked I, Joell Ortiz, Royce da 5'9\", and Joe Budden appeared on the song \"Slaughterhouse\" from Joe Budden's album ''[[Halfway House (album)|Halfway House]]''. They decided to form a group and named the group after the song. The members of Slaughterhouse all share some degree of controversy from their past in the music industry. All four address these issues in the song \"Move On\".\n\n===2009\u20132010: Debut album===\nTheir self-titled debut album was released on August 11, 2009. The album was recorded over a six-day period in early June. The album features production from Focus,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebossboard.com/article.php?newid=176 |title=Slaughterhouse Confirms The E1 Deal |publisher=The B.O.S.S. Board |accessdate=2011-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6HIQT0MeD?url=http://www.thebossboard.com/article.php?newid=176 |archivedate=2013-06-11 }}</ref> [[The Alchemist (producer)|The Alchemist]], [[DJ Khalil]], StreetRunner and [[Mr. Porter]] of [[D12]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Koroma |first=Salima |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9213 |title=More Details Emerge About Slaughterhouse Debut &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-05-28 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> On June 18, 2009, the first street single off the album was released via Joe Budden's Twitter account. The track was \"Woodstock (Hood Hop)\" and features [[M.O.P.]] on the hook.<ref name=\"Rock The Bells Tour\">{{cite web|url=http://www.welivethis.com/newsfeed/2009/06/25/slaughterhouse-featuring-mop-hood-hop-woodstock-cdq/ |title=Slaughterhouse - Rock The Bells Tour Dates and Release of Hood Hop |work=WeLiveThis.com |accessdate=June 25, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090703060118/http://www.welivethis.com/newsfeed/2009/06/25/slaughterhouse-featuring-mop-hood-hop-woodstock-cdq/ |archivedate=July 3, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[http://yaheardhiphop.blogspot.com/2009/06/first-leak-off-slaughterhouses-debut.html] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090713091753/http://yaheardhiphop.blogspot.com/2009/06/first-leak-off-slaughterhouses-debut.html|date=July 13, 2009}}</ref> The first official single from the album was \"[[The One (Slaughterhouse song)|The One]]\". A second video for the song ''Microphone'' was also released in late 2009. A video directed by [[Rik Cordero]].\n\nTheir debut album sold 18,000 copies in its first week (Only 20,000 copies were shipped to stores).<ref>{{cite web|last=Paine |first=Jake |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9660 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 8/16/2009 &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-08-19 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> As of September 5, 2009 the album has sold 31,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jacobs |first=Allen |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9774 |title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 9/5/2009 &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-09-09 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref>\n\nThe group initially planned for their second album to release in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|last=Vasquez |first=Andres |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9621 |title=Slaughterhouse Talk Second Album And 2010 Plans &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2009-08-12 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> tentatively named by Crooked I as ''No Muzzle''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://allhiphop.com/stories/features/archive/2009/10/28/22000800.aspx |title=Features : Crooked I: Slaughterhouse Superman |publisher=Allhiphop.com |date= |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> In late 2009, however, [[Royce da 5'9\"]] confirmed talks between the group and [[Shady Records]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/slaughterhouse/092909-royce-da-59-confirms-that-his-slaughterhouse-group-is-in-talks-with-eminem-and-shady-records.html |title=Royce Confirms Negotiations With Shady Records &#124; Slaughterhouse |publisher=Rap Basement |date=2009-09-29 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Reid |first=Shaheem |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1622494/20090928/eminem.jhtml |title=Are Slaughterhouse Joining Eminem's Shady Records? 'It Would Be A Great Thing,' Royce Da 5'9\" Says - Music, Celebrity, Artist News |publisher=MTV |date=2009-09-28 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> stating that he felt their second album should be released on a major label.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapbasement.com/royce-59/112709-royce-da-5-9-talks-about-slaughterhouse-future-and-plans-to-sign-with-a-major-label-watch-her.html |title=Royce Talks Slaughterhouse's Future &#124; Royce 59 |publisher=Rap Basement |date=2009-11-27 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref>\n\n===2011\u20132012: Shady Records and ''Welcome to: Our House''===\nAs rumors of a [[Shady Records]]/Slaughterhouse signing spread, in March 2010, Joell Ortiz posted a rant on Twitter denigrating E1 Entertainment for blocking Shady negotiations, implying that another party was involved as well. Responding to a disgruntled Amalgam Digital executive's allegations against him, Joe Budden confirmed that complications regarding E1 and Amalgam were the reason the deal had not been completed previously.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://musiconplay.net/25/03/2010/joe-budden-responds-to-amalgam-explains-slaughterhouseshady-delay/ |title=Joe Budden Responds To Amalgam, Explains Slaughterhouse/Shady Delay &#124; Music On Play - We The Best FOREVER |publisher=Music On Play |date= |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> Royce da 5'9\" would later name-drop Shady Records in a ''Bar Exam 3'' freestyle,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ballerstatus.com/2010/03/31/royce-da-59-hints-at-slaughterhouseshady-records-deal/ |title=Royce Da 5'9 Hints At Slaughterhouse/Shady Records Deal |publisher=Ballerstatus |date=2010-03-31 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> and the group released a song entitled \"Beamer, Benz or Bentley (ShadyMegaMix)\", while still with E1.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=77089 |title=Slaughterhouse \"Beamer, Benz or Bentley (Shady Megamix)\" |website=XXLmag.com |accessdate=April 22, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424193046/http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=77089 |archivedate=April 24, 2010 }}</ref> Slaughterhouse, minus Joe Budden, were featured on the iTunes deluxe edition of Eminem's [[Recovery (Eminem album)|Recovery]] album on the track \"Session One\", while also still with E1. The group also featured in \"Loud Noises\" on ''[[Hell: The Sequel]]'', a collaborative EP between Royce and Eminem.\n\nPlans to release an EP were revealed by HipHopDX in their Rap Release Dates update in June 2010, tentatively titled ''[[Slaughterhouse EP]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hanna |first=Mitchell |url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.11540 |title=Wednesday Rap Release Dates: Schoolly D, Curren$y, Bun B &#124; Get The Latest Hip Hop News, Rap News & Hip Hop Album Sales |publisher=HipHopDX |date=2010-06-23 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref> The EP was released on February 8, 2011, with four new tracks and two remixes by Frequency of tracks previously released. On January 12, 2011, it was confirmed that the group officially signed to [[Shady Records]] along with [[Yelawolf]]. Both acts appeared along with [[Eminem]] on the cover of ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' magazine's March 2011 edition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rapradar.com/2011/01/12/eminem-covers-xxl-signs-slaughterhouse-yelawolf/ |title=Eminem Covers XXL; Signs Slaughterhouse & Yelawolf |publisher=Rap Radar |date=2011-01-12 |accessdate=2011-03-01}}</ref>\n\nA year later, the group was featured on the cover of the July/August issue of ''The Source'' magazine in anticipation of their Shady Records debut.<ref>{{cite web|last=Osorio |first=Kim |url=http://thesource.com/2012/06/19/slaughterhouseandbeastieboyscoverthenewissueofthesource/ |title=Slaughterhouse and Beastie Boys Cover The New Issue Of The Source |publisher=The Source |date=2012-06-19}}</ref> On July 7, 2012, Royce announced in an interview with Jenny Boom Boom that the group will release a pre-album mixtape around the first week of August. A new single \"Throw It Away\" produced by Swizz Beats, will be off the album \"Welcome to: Our House\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W6ahjiy6ZRI&feature=player_embedded|title=Jenny Boom Boom Interviews Slaughterhouse @ BET Awards 12|publisher=Jenny Boom Boom |accessdate=2012-07-07}}</ref> Joe Budden revealed via Twitter that the mixtape is called \"On The House\" and will be hosted by DJ Drama.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JoeBudden/status/229020898190041088 |title=Twitter / JoeBudden: Real shit tho, the verses on |publisher=Twitter.com |date= |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> A promotional video for the mixtape was released on August 6, 2012 and previewed a song called \"See Dead People\", with confirmed guest appearances on the mixtape by [[Eminem]] and [[Black Hippy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thebossboard.com/article.php?newid=1189 |title=Slaughterhouse Officially Announces Mixtape |publisher=The B.O.S.S. Board |date= |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> On August 16, Slaughterhouse released a new track, \"Truth or Truth\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zPBCA41wGHw |title=Slaughterhouse - Truth Or Truth (On The House) |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-08-16 |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> The Mixtape ''[[On the House (album)|On the House]]'' was released on Aug.19th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/Slaughterhouse-On-The-House-mixtape.381972.html |title=Slaughterhouse - On The House Hosted by DJ Drama // Free Mixtape @ |publisher=Datpiff.com |date=2012-08-19 |accessdate=2012-09-01}}</ref> Slaughterhouse released their second studio album ''[[Welcome to: Our House]]'', the first to be released under Shady Records, on August 28, 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.18435|title=Slaughterhouse Announces Shady Records Debut ''Welcome to: Our House,''  Tour Dates|publisher=HipHopDX |accessdate=2012-01-26}}</ref> As of November 23, 2012, it has sold 146,000 copies in the US. Budden has admitted to the group abusing substances during the recording of the album however saying the whole group is sober and ready for their third album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.22273/title.joe-budden-excited-to-work-on-slaughterhouses-next-album-while-sober/|title=Joe Budden Excited To Work On Slaughterhouse's Next Album While Sober|author=HipHopDX|date=19 December 2012|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2013-2018: ''Glass House'' and split ===\nIn May 2013, Slaughterhouse confirmed that they had put their solo projects on hold, and had begun recording for their third studio album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/05/slaughterhouse-getting-started-with-the-recording-process-for-new-album/ |title=Slaughterhouse \u201cGetting Started With The Recording Process\u201d For New Album - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref> The album will be executive produced by [[Just Blaze]] and contains production by [[J.U.S.T.I.C.E. League]], [[Cardiak]], [[Illmind]], [[AraabMuzik]] and [[DJ Premier]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.23466/title.just-blaze-said-to-executive-produce-slaughterhouse-s-third-album-|title=Just Blaze Said To Executive Produce Slaughterhouse's Third Album|author=HipHopDX|date=18 June 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2013/07/joell-ortiz-the-object-is-to-make-slaughterhouse-one-person/ |title=Joell Ortiz: \u201cThe Object Is To Make Slaughterhouse One Person\u201d - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref> In November 2013, Joe Budden confirmed that the album would be released in early 2014. At the time he also stated that [[Action Bronson]] would be featured on the album, and they had yet to work with Eminem on it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.26219/title.joe-budden-discusses-slaughterhouse-s-upcoming-album-action-bronson-collaboration|title=Joe Budden Discusses Slaughterhouse's Upcoming Album & Action Bronson Collaboration|author=HipHopDX|date=12 November 2013|work=HipHopDX|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> On May 21, 2014, the group released their second mixtape titled ''[[House Rules (mixtape)|House Rules]]'', which featured 10 tracks with production from [[Nottz]], [[AraabMuzik]], [[DJ Pain 1]], [[The Heatmakerz]], [[Illmind]], [[Harry Fraud]] among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.datpiff.com/houserules|title=Slaughterhouse - House Rules|work=DatPiff|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> On February 19, 2015, Royce Da 5'9\" had confirmed that the album was \"pretty close to being done\", and that the group, along with Eminem were \"nitpicking at it\". He had hoped for a summer release date for the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlive.com/entertainment/detroit/index.ssf/2015/02/detroits_royce_da_59_says_slau.html|title=Detroit's Royce da 5'9\" says Slaughterhouse's 'Glass House' album is 'pretty close to being done'|author=Eric Stacy|date=February 19, 2015|accessdate=May 18, 2015}}</ref> On February 7, 2017, Joe Budden confirmed on his podcast that the album will never be released<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/news/2017/02/joe-budden-new-slaughterhouse-album-never-coming-out/ |title=Joe Budden Says Album Slaughterhouse Recorded Years Ago Is Never Coming Out - XXL |publisher=Xxlmag.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Kxng Crooked announced via Instagram his departure from Slaughterhouse and confirmed that ''Glass House'' \"exists\" but without a release date. He said there were no harsh feelings about his departure: it was \"all love\". Joell Ortiz and Royce da 5'9\" commented on the announcement with respect and support. On April 26, 2018, Royce da 5\u20199\u201d announced that the supergroup had officially disbanded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hiphopwired.com/750854/royce-da-59-confirms-that-slaughterhouse-is-done/|title=Royce Da 5\u20199\u2033 Confirms That Slaughterhouse is \u201cDone\u201d}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Eminem released a four-part interview with SWAY on his YouTube channel explaining the reasons why the group had a downfall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wrpauWGy4tQ|title=Eminem x Sway - The Kamikaze Interview (Part 2)|date=September 12, 2018|website=YouTube}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, the group (minus Joe Budden)  was featured on [[Eminem]]'s eleventh studio album [[Music to Be Murdered By|Music to be Murdered By]] on the track \"I Will\".<ref>https://genius.com/Eminem-i-will-lyrics</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Slaughterhouse discography}}\n\n* ''[[Slaughterhouse (Slaughterhouse album)|Slaughterhouse]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[Welcome to: Our House]]'' (2012)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Slaughterhouse}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Slaughterhouse members templates\n|list1=\n{{Crooked I}}\n{{Joe Budden}}\n{{Joell Ortiz}}\n{{Royce da 5'9\"}}\n}}\n{{Shady Records}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slaughterhouse (group)}}\n[[Category:Hip hop supergroups]]\n[[Category:American hip hop groups]]\n[[Category:Shady Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2018]]\n", "name_user": "Eminem's Biggest Fan (Stan)", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slaughterhouse_(group)"}
{"title_page": "Niko Hovinen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| alt = \n| name = Niko Hovinen\n| image = 2015-03-21 Leksands IF\u2013Malm\u00f6 Redhawks Niko Hovinen 01.jpg\n| image_size = 230px\n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1988|03|16}}\n| birth_place = [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 7\n| weight_lb = 200\n| position = [[Goaltender]]\n| catches = Left\n| league = [[Liiga]]\n| team = [[Vaasan Sport]]\n| former_teams = [[Jokerit]]<br>[[Lahti Pelicans|Pelicans]]<br>[[Oklahoma City Barons]]<br>[[Metallurg Novokuznetsk]]<br>[[Admiral Vladivostok]]<br>[[EC Red Bull Salzburg]]<br>[[Lule\u00e5 HF]]<br>[[Oulun K\u00e4rp\u00e4t]]<br>[[KHL Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb|Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb]]<br>[[KalPa]]<br>[[KooKoo (Liiga)|KooKoo]]<br>[[Lausanne HC]]<br>[[Iserlohn Roosters]]\n| ntl_team = Finland\n| draft = 132nd overall\n| draft_year = 2006\n| draft_team = [[Minnesota Wild]]\n| career_start = 2005\n}}\n\n'''Niko Hovinen''' (born 16 March 1988) is a [[Finnish people|Finnish]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]]. He is currently playing with [[Vaasan Sport]] of the [[Liiga]].\n\n==Playing career==\n\n===Jokerit===\nNiko Hovinen's SM-liiga career started during the 2005\u201306 season when Hovinen dressed for a single regular-season Jokerit game as backup to [[Joonas Hallikainen]], after [[Tim Thomas (ice hockey)|Tim Thomas]] abruptly left the team only a day before the start of the 2005\u201306 regular season. Hovinen returned to the junior team for the rest of the season. He made his first SM-liiga start on 23 November 2006, against [[SaiPa]], again called up when three Jokerit goaltenders were injured.\n\nDuring the 2007\u201308 season, Hovinen served as backup to [[Jussi Markkanen]]. Hovinen was relegated to no. 3 goaltender when Jokerit acquired [[Joni Puurula]] from [[SaiPa]] just before the end of regular season. Hovinen dressed up to serve as backup for Joni Puurula in several games during the 2007\u201308 playoffs as Jussi Markkanen got himself injured during the first game of playoffs.\n\n===Pelicans===\nDuring the off-season of 2007\u201308 SM-liiga season, Niko Hovinen was contracted to [[Lahti Pelicans|Pelicans]]. For the first time, Niko Hovinen will play outside of Jokerit-organization in 2008\u201309 season.\n\nA tall goaltender at 196&nbsp;cm, Hovinen covers the net very well and is considered a highly promising goaltender prospect.{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}\n[[File:Niko Hovinen - OKC Barons (1).jpg|thumb|left|200px|Niko Hovinen with the [[Oklahoma City Barons]].]]\nHovinen was ranked #10 on the International Scouting Service's list of goaltender prospects for the [[2006 NHL Entry Draft]]. He was drafted in the fifth round, 132nd overall, by the [[Minnesota Wild]].\n\n===North America===\nHovinen signed a two-year entry level contract with the [[National Hockey League]]'s [[Philadelphia Flyers]] on 17 May 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://flyers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=563023|title=Flyers sign (G) Hivonen|date=2011-05-17|accessdate=2011-05-17|publisher=philadelphiaflyers.com}}</ref> He remained with the [[Lahti Pelicans|Pelicans]] through the 2011\u201312 season.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.csnphilly.com/05/17/11/Flyers-sign-goalie-Hovinen-to-entry-leve/news_flyers.html?blockID=524112&feedID=704|title=Flyers sign goalie Hovinen to entry-level contract|date=2011-05-17|accessdate=2011-05-17|author=Sarah Baicker|publisher=CSNPhilly.com|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120724015927/http://www.csnphilly.com/05/17/11/Flyers-sign-goalie-Hovinen-to-entry-leve/news_flyers.html?blockID=524112&feedID=704|archivedate=24 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 2013 the [[Edmonton Oilers]] claimed Hovinen off unconditional waivers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oilers.nhl.com/club/news.htm?id=652402|title=Oilers claim G Niko Hovinen off waivers from the Philadelphia Flyers - Edmonton Oilers - Transactions|date=2013-01-25|accessdate=2013-01-25|publisher=edmontonoilers.com}}</ref> He was assigned to AHL affiliate, the [[Oklahoma City Barons]], where he remained to end the [[2013-14 AHL season|2013\u201314]] season.\n\n=== Back to Europe ===\nOn 2 July 2013, Hovinen's NHL rights were retained by the Oilers after he was tendered a qualifying offer. He opted to return to Europe signing a contract with [[Metallurg Novokuznetsk]] of the [[Kontinental Hockey League]] (KHL), before moving on to fellow KHL team [[Admiral Vladivostok]].\n\nHe split the [[2014-15 SHL season|2014\u201315]] season between [[EC Red Bull Salzburg|EC Salzburg]] of Austria and Swedish teams [[Lule\u00e5 HF]] and [[Malm\u00f6 Redhawks]]. In the 2015\u201316 campaign, Hovinen was back in his native Finland for a second stint with the [[Lahti Pelicans|Pelicans]]. On 13 June 2016, he put pen to paper on a deal with [[KHL Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb|Medvescak Zagreb]] of the [[Kontinental Hockey League]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.medvescak.com/en/khl/finn-hovinen-will-be-in-goal-in-zagreb%E2%80%99s-den-no2360|title=Finn Hovinen will be in goal in Zagreb\u2019s Den| website = www.medvescak.com|access-date=2016-06-25}}</ref> and parted ways with the club in November 2016. Later that month, he was picked up by [[KalPa]] of the Finnish top-flight [[Liiga]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kalpa.fi/2016-2017_uutinen/eero-kilpelainen-sivussa-jouluun-asti-niko-hovinen-kalpa-paitaan|title=Uutiset - Eero Kilpel\u00e4inen sivussa jouluun asti, Niko Hovinen KalPa-paitaan| website = www.kalpa.fi|access-date=2016-11-15}}</ref> Following a stint at fellow Liiga outfit [[KooKoo (Liiga)|KooKoo]], he signed with [[Lausanne HC]] of the Swiss [[National League A|NLA]] on February 7, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lausannehc.ch/nouvelle-arrivee/|title=Nouvelle arriv\u00e9e. - Lausanne Hockey Club|last=Club|first=Lausanne Hockey| website = www.lausannehc.ch|language=fr-FR|access-date=2017-02-07}}</ref>\n\nA free agent from his [[2018-19 DEL season|2018\u201319]] season stint in the [[Deutsche Eishockey Liga]] with the [[Iserlohn Roosters]], Hovinen familiarly returned to the Ligga, agreeing to a one-year contract with Vaasan Sport on 7 October 2019.<ref>{{citeweb| url = https://vaasansport.fi/fi-fi/article/uutinen/niko-hovinen-sportin-maalille/5156/ | title = Niko Hovinen signs with Sport | publisher = [[Vaasan Sport]] | date = 7 October 2019 | accessdate = 7 October 2019 | language = Finnish}}</ref>\n{{MedalTableTop| name = |File:Niko Hovinen.png |200px }}\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagicon|FIN}} [[Finland]]}}\n{{MedalSport|[[Ice hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Ice Hockey World Championships|World Championships]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 IIHF World Championship|2011]] [[Slovakia]]|}}\n{{MedalBottom}}\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Regular season and playoffs===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:75%\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! align=\"center\" rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"9\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" | [[Regular season]]\n! align=\"center\" rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" |  \n! align=\"center\" colspan=\"8\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" | [[Playoffs]]\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! [[Season (sports)|Season]]\n! Team\n! League\n! GP\n! W\n! L\n! T/OT\n! MIN\n! GA\n! [[Shutout#Ice hockey|SO]]\n! [[Goals against average|GAA]]\n! [[save percentage|SV%]]\n! GP\n! W\n! L\n! MIN\n! GA\n! SO\n! GAA\n! SV%\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| [[2006\u201307 SM-liiga season|2006\u201307]]\n| [[Jokerit]]\n| [[SM-liiga|SM-l]]\n| 1\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n| 60\n| 4\n| 0\n| 4.00\n| .871\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| [[2007\u201308 SM-liiga season|2007\u201308]]\n| Jokerit\n| SM-l\n| 4\n| 0\n| 1\n| 0\n| 125\n| 12\n| 0\n| 5.78\n| .833\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|