\n! 2.58\n! .920\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{icehockeystats}}\n* [http://www.jatkoaika.com/smliiga.php?pelaaja=4798 Jatkoaika.com player profile (in Finnish)]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hovinen, Niko}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish ice hockey goaltenders]]\n[[Category:Admiral Vladivostok players]]\n[[Category:Iserlohn Roosters players]]\n[[Category:Jokerit players]]\n[[Category:KalPa players]]\n[[Category:KooKoo players]]\n[[Category:Lahti Pelicans players]]\n[[Category:Lausanne HC players]]\n[[Category:Lule\u00e5 HF players]]\n[[Category:Malm\u00f6 Redhawks players]]\n[[Category:KHL Medve\u0161\u010dak Zagreb players]]\n[[Category:Metallurg Novokuznetsk players]]\n[[Category:Minnesota Wild draft picks]]\n[[Category:Oklahoma City Barons players]]\n[[Category:Oulun K\u00e4rp\u00e4t players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:EC Red Bull Salzburg players]]\n[[Category:Trenton Titans players]]\n[[Category:Vaasan Sport players]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: 2005-06 \u2192 2005\u201306 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Niko_Hovinen"}
{"title_page": "The Song of the Volga Boatmen", "text_new": "[[File:Ilia Efimovich Repin (1844-1930) - Volga Boatmen (1870-1873).jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Ilya Yefimovich Repin]]'s painting ''[[Barge Haulers on the Volga]]'']]\n{{Listen|filename=\u042d\u0439,_\u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!_-_\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440_\u0428\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043f\u0438\u043d.ogg|title=\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c'' / The Song of the Volga Boatmen|description=1902 record by Feodor Chaliapin|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\nThe \"'''Song of the Volga Boatmen'''\" (known in [[Russian language|Russian]] as '''\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!''' [Ey, ukhnem!, \"yo, heave-ho!\"], after the refrain) is a well-known traditional [[Russia]]n song collected by [[Mily Balakirev]], and published in his book of folk songs in 1866.<ref>{{cite book|\ntitle=The book of world-famous music: classical, popular, and folk\n|first=James J.|last=Fuld|page=520|publisher=Courier Dover|year=2000}}</ref> It was sung by [[burlak]]s, or barge-haulers, on the [[Volga River]]. Balakirev published it with only one verse (the first). The other two verses were added at a later date. [[Ilya Repin]]'s famous painting ''[[Barge Haulers on the Volga]]'' depicts such burlaks in [[Russian Empire|Tsarist Russia]] toiling along the Volga.\n\nThe song was popularised by [[Feodor Chaliapin]], and has been a favourite concert piece of bass singers ever since. [[Bill Finegan]]'s jazz arrangement for the [[Glenn Miller]] band took the song to #1 in the US charts in 1941. Russian composer [[Alexander Glazunov]] based one of the themes of his symphonic poem \"Stenka Razin\" on the song. Spanish composer [[Manuel De Falla]] wrote an arrangement of the song, which was published under the name ''Canto de los remeros del Volga (del cancionero musical ruso)'' in 1922.<ref name=hess>Hess, Carol A. ''Sacred Passions: The Life and Music of Manuel de Falla'', Oxford University Press, 2005, p. 134. {{ISBN|0-19-514561-5}}.</ref> He did so at the behest of diplomat [[Ricardo Baeza (diplomat)|Ricardo Baeza]], who was working with the [[League of Nations]] to provide financial relief for the more than two million Russian refugees who had been displaced and imprisoned during [[World War I]].<ref name=hess /> All proceeds from the song's publication were donated to this effort.<ref name=hess /> [[Igor Stravinsky]] made an arrangement for orchestra.\n\n== First publications and recordings ==\nA version of the song was recorded by [[Mily Balakirev]] (a Russian composer) from Nikolay Aleynikov in [[Nizhny Novgorod]] in 1860 or 1861. Already in 1866, the musician published it in his book ''A collection of Russian folk songs'' by {{nowrap|M. Balakirev}} ({{lang-ru|\t\n\u00ab\u0421\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a\u044a \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445\u044a \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445\u044a \u043f\u0463\u0441\u0435\u043d\u044a\u00bb}}; 1866), with his own arrangement.<ref name=\"\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u04411962\">{{cite book|author=\u0415. \u0412. \u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u0441|language=ru|title=\"\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c\": \"\u0414\u0443\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0430\" : \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=S0wIAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0|year=1962|publisher=\u0421\u043e\u0432. \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|language=ru|title=\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0418\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0463\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0456\u044e \u044d\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0456\u0438|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gd45AQAAMAAJ&q=%22%D0%A1%D0%B1%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D1%8A+%D1%80%D1%83%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BD%D1%8B%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BF%D1%A3%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8A%22+1866&dq=%22%D0%A1%D0%B1%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D1%8A+%D1%80%D1%83%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BD%D1%8B%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BF%D1%A3%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8A%22+1866&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_sZLEoJ_aAhUMCZoKHQ0EBtkQ6AEIKzAB}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438|language=ru|author=\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u0441, \u0415. \u0412.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&id=Qj0JAQAAMAAJ&dq=%D0%B1%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B2+%D0%B4%D1%83%D0%B1%D0%B8%D0%BD%D1%83%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%B0+%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B6%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B9+%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B3%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%D0%90%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%B9%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B0}}</ref>\n\nProbably, the first released version of the song was recorded in Russia in 1900 by Alexander Makarov-Yunev ({{lang-ru|{{nowrap|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432-\u042e\u043d\u0435\u0432}}}}) on [[Gramophone Company|Gramophone]] (#22086).<ref>{{cite book|author1=\u0413\u0440\u044e\u043d\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u041f. \u041d.|author2=\u042f\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0412. \u041b.|author2-link=Valentin Yanin|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0437\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438. \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \"\u0413\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u043e\u0444\u043e\u043d\"|location=\u041c.|language=ru|publisher=\u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b|pages=235|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qr1GAAAAMAAJ&q=22086+%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22&dq=22086+%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVgujywZ7aAhXJECwKHcDeA38Q6AEIJDAA}}</ref>\n\n== Lyrics ==\n{| cellpadding=6\n! Russian\n! Transliteration\n! (Poetic) English translation\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0451\u0437\u0443,\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u043a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0443!\n:\u0410\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:A\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u043a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0443.\n\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u043a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0443.\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n\n:\u041c\u044b \u043f\u043e \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0443 \u0438\u0434\u0451\u043c,\n:\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0451\u043c.\n:\u0410\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:A\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0451\u043c.\n\n:\u042d\u0439, \u044d\u0439, \u0442\u044f\u043d\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0439!\n:\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0451\u043c.\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n\n:\u042d\u0445 \u0442\u044b, \u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0430, \u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c-\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0430,\n:\u0428\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0433\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u043a\u0430,\n:\u0410\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:A\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0430, \u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0430, \u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c-\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0430\n\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n|\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n\n:Razovyom my byeryozu,\n:Razovyom my kudryavu!\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Razovyom my kudryavu.\n\n:Razovyom my kudryavu.\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n\n:My po byeryezhku idyom,\n:Pyesnyu solnyshku poyom.\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Pyesnyu solnyshku poyom.\n\n:Ey, Ey, tyani kanat silney!\n:Pyesnyu solnyshku poyom.\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n\n:Ekh, ty, Volga, mat'-reka,\n:Shiroka i gluboka,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Volga, Volga, mat'-reka\n\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n|\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n\n:Now we fell the stout birch tree,\n:Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n\n:Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n\n:As we walk along the shore,\n:To the sun we sing our song.\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:To the sun we sing our song.\n\n:Hey, hey, let's heave a-long the way\n:To the sun we sing our song\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n\n:Oh, you, Volga, mother river,\n:Mighty stream so deep and wide.\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Volga, Volga, mother river.\n\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n|}\n\nThe English lyrics above fit the melody. A more accurate translation of some lines are:\n{| cellpadding=6\n! Poetic\n! Literal\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n| Now we fell the stout birch tree,\n| We'll untwist the stout birch tree,\n|-\n| Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n| We'll untwist the curly tree!\n|-\n| Hey, hey, let's heave a-long the way\n| Hey, hey, pull this way!\n|-\n| Mighty stream so deep and wide.\n| Wide and deep,\n|}\n\n== Notable recordings and arrangements ==\nThe song was arranged by [[Feodor Koenemann]] for [[Chaliapin]]. That Chaliapin's version became one of the most popular in Russia and has been released several times (e.g., in 1922, 1927, 1936).<ref name=\"\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u04411962\"/><ref>{{cite book|editor={{nowrap|\u0415. \u0410. \u0413\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0430}}|volume=II|pages=516, 517, 519|title=\u0428\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043f\u0438\u043d|publisher=\u0418\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|location=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430|year=1960|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nIn 1905, [[Alexander Glazunov]] created his piece ''Ey, ukhnem'' based on the Balakirev's tune.<ref name=\"\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u04411962\"/><ref name=\"\u0412\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043b\u043e\u04321950\">{{cite book|author=\u0412\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432, \u0412. \u0412.|title=\u0421\u0438\u043c\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0410.\u041a. \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0437\u0443\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3cguAAAAIAAJ&q=%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22+%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B7%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2+1905&dq=%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22+%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B7%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2+1905&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZsb_i-6HaAhXOZpoKHdyuBQw4HhDoAQhDMAc|year=1950|language=ru|publisher=\u0413\u043e\u0441. \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0434-\u0432\u043e}}</ref>\n\nCzech composer [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nov\u00e1k]] utilizes the main motif from ''Song of the Volga Boatmen'' in his ''M\u00e1jov\u00e1 symfonie'' (''May Symphony'', Op.&nbsp;73, 1943), for soloists, mixed chorus, and orchestra.\n\nA translated vocal version was sung by [[Paul Robeson]].\n\nThe [[Boston Pops Orchestra]] conducted by [[Arthur Fiedler]] recorded the Glazunov arrangement of the tune in New York City on June 30, 1937.\n\nThe song, or at least the tune, was popularized in the mid-20th Century through an instrumental jazz version played by the [[Glenn Miller Band]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJRts1kwzKc YouTube: The Song of the Volga Boatmen].</ref> Glenn Miller released the song as an RCA Bluebird 78 single, B-11029-A, in 1941 in a swing jazz arrangement by Bill Finegan which reached no. 1 on the ''Billboard'' pop singles chart in a 10-week chart run.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoffmann|first1=Frank|title=Chronology of American Popular Music, 1900-2000|date=May 23, 2016|publisher=Routledge|location=London; New York|isbn=978-0-415-97715-9|page=93|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hAI3DAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref> Not in copyright, the song was not subject to the 1941 [[ASCAP boycott]], allowing for more radio play that year.<ref name=pc2b>{{Pop Chronicles 40s|2|B |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc1633220/m1/#track/2}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965, [[Leonid Kharitonov (singer)|Leonid Kharitonov]], together with the Russian [[Alexandrov Ensemble|Red Army Choir]], released a recording.\n\nThe Swedish jazz pianist [[Jan Johansson (jazz musician)|Jan Johansson]] arranged an instrumental version for jazz trio (Pr\u00e5mdragarnas s\u00e5ng vid Volga) on his album \"Jazz P\u00e5 Ryska\"(1967).<ref>http://www.janjohansson.org/jpr.html</ref>\n\n== Modern popular culture ==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:Song of Volga Boatmen Glenn Miller 11029.jpg|thumb|1941 recording by Glenn Miller, RCA Bluebird, B-11029-A.]]\nThe memorable melody of ''The Song of the Volga Boatmen'' has led to its common usage in many musical situations, particularly as background music, often with the theme of unremitting toil (or, alternatively, devotion to duty). Some uses, particularly those portending doom or despair, employ only the iconic four-note beginning; others go so far as to add new, often wryly humorous, lyrics, such as the \"Birthday Dirge\".<ref>[http://www.faqs.org/faqs/music/birthday-dirge-faq/ The Birthday Dirge].</ref> Some usages only acknowledge the tune's Russian heritage; very few use the original lyrics (for instance its use as the introductory theme of the Soviet boxer, [[Soda Popinski]], in ''[[Mike Tyson's Punch-Out!!]]'').\n\nInstances include:\n* The cartoon ''[[Goofy Gymnastics]]'' (1949)\n* [[Dickie Goodman]] in his 1959 novelty hit \"Russian Bandstand.\"\n* At 2:55 minutes in the song \"[[The Stroke]]\" by [[Billy Squier]].\n* In ''[[A Troll in Central Park]]'', a minor character sings \"I'm a bad troll, a very bad troll!\" to the tune.\n* The [[Fremantle Football Club]] of the [[Australian Football League]] based their inaugural club song on the tune, used between 1995 and 2011.\n* The Gainesville, Florida rock band [[The Vulgar Boatmen]] were named as a play on the original term.\n* [[Peter Schickele]] (writing as ''P D Q Bach'') used the tune for the subject of a [[fugue]] called \"Fuga Vulgaris\" in [[List of works by P. D. Q. Bach|Toot Suite for Calliope four hands]].\n* On the ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The Springfield Files]]\", when Homer takes the [[breathalyzer]] test, he reaches level \"[[Boris Yeltsin]]\", which then plays the song's tune.\n* On two episodes of ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'': in \"Sandy, SpongeBob, and the Worm\", the song can be heard as Patrick and the townspeople push the city of Bikini Bottom; in \"Employee of the Month\", the song is heard as SpongeBob and Squidward crawl to the Krusty Krab \n* In the 2001 film ''[[Shrek]]'', the tune of the song is hummed by the dwarves as they are being led away in [[chain]]s. \n* The tune is used in 'Shirley Whirley' episode of ''[[Shaun the Sheep]]'' cartoon.\n* A piece by [[Gramatik]] (Denis Jasarevic), 'The Swing of Justice' (2014) reuses the Glenn Miller piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://pro.beatport.com/track/the-swing-of-justice-original-mix/5125911|title = Gramatik - The Swing Of Justice|date = |accessdate = 2015-05-14|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The song was used in the film ''[[Lord of War]]'' when Yuri is in [[Ukraine]] purchasing Soviet military hardware from his uncle after the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|breakup of the USSR]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Niccol|first=Andrew|title=Lord of War|date=2005-09-16|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0399295/soundtrack|accessdate=2016-05-28}}</ref>\n* The 1944 [[Warner Bros.]] cartoon ''[[Russian Rhapsody (film)|Russian Rhapsody]]'' features [[gremlin]]s dismantling [[Adolf Hitler]]'s [[airplane]]. They sing \"We are gremlins from the [[Kremlin]]\" to the tune of the song.\n* On the ''[[Gilligan's Island]]'' episode \"Goodbye, Old Paint\", a Russian artist ([[Harold J. Stone]]) sings the song while painting, occasionally making up his own lyrics.\n* The song was featured in the film ''[[Tovarich (film)|Tovarich]]'' (1937).\n*The theme of the Russian civilization in the series ''[[Civilization (series)|Civilization]]'', including the [[Sid Meier's Civilization|original game]] and its sequels ''[[Civilization II]]'' and ''[[Civilization IV]]''.\n* In [[Team Fortress 2]], the character Heavy can be heard singing the song at times.<ref>http://www.tf2sounds.com/1793#q%3Dsing</ref><ref>http://www.tf2sounds.com/475#q%3Dsing</ref>\n* The melody of the song is featured in [[Tetris: Axis]] for [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* A rendition of the song is played in [[Pipe Mania]] for [[NES]] whenever a level is failed, or the game is over.\n* Parts of the song are used in the Malinovka map theme of [[World of Tanks]].\n* The video game [[Punch-Out!! (Wii)]] features the song in Russian character Soda Popinski's introductory cutscenes. It is also used to introduce him in the earlier [[Punch-Out!! (NES)|Nintendo Entertainment System version]].\n* The Fremantle Dockers (An Australian Rules Football club) used to base the official club song off of The Volga Boatmen until sections were removed.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons|File:\u042d\u0439,_\u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!_-_\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440_\u0428\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043f\u0438\u043d.ogg|The Song of the Volga Boatmen}}\n* [[List of number-one singles of 1941 (U.S.)]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SRe1dsXs6_s YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen]: Performed by Kovcheg Aca Pella; Five males, including two basso profundo.\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Song of the Volga Boatmen (Balakirev, Mily)|cname=Song of the Volga Boatmen}}.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8WD0WVL-HjE&feature=channel_page YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 sung in the tradition of [[Feodor Chaliapin|Chaliapin]] by [[Leonid Kharitonov (singer)|Leonid Kharitonov]] with the [[Alexandrov Ensemble]], 1965.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KfsWoNpHg2s YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 [[Paul Robeson]].\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfigZBtAIjs YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 [[Glenn Miller]] and his orchestra.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LMbuUUk_3f4 YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 translated Chinese version performed by the Male Choir of the People's Armed Police.\n\n{{Glenn Miller}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Song of the Volga Boatmen, The}}\n[[Category:Russian folk songs]]\n[[Category:Sea shanties]]\n[[Category:Songs about rivers]]\n[[Category:Songs about boats]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n[[Category:Feodor Chaliapin songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about Russia]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Ilia Efimovich Repin (1844-1930) - Volga Boatmen (1870-1873).jpg|thumb|250px|right|[[Ilya Yefimovich Repin]]'s painting ''[[Barge Haulers on the Volga]]'']]\n{{Listen|filename=\u042d\u0439,_\u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!_-_\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440_\u0428\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043f\u0438\u043d.ogg|title=\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c'' / The Song of the Volga Boatmen|description=1902 record by Feodor Chaliapin|format=[[Ogg]]}}\n\nThe \"'''Song of the Volga Boatmen'''\" (known in [[Russian language|Russian]] as '''\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!''' [Ey, ukhnem!, \"yo, heave-ho!\"], after the refrain) is a well-known traditional [[Russia]]n song collected by [[Mily Balakirev]], and published in his book of folk songs in 1866.<ref>{{cite book|\ntitle=The book of world-famous music: classical, popular, and folk\n|first=James J.|last=Fuld|page=520|publisher=Courier Dover|year=2000}}</ref> It was sung by [[burlak]]s, or barge-haulers, on the [[Volga River]]. Balakirev published it with only one verse (the first). The other two verses were added at a later date. [[Ilya Repin]]'s famous painting ''[[Barge Haulers on the Volga]]'' depicts such burlaks in [[Russian Empire|Tsarist Russia]] toiling along the Volga.\n\nThe song was popularised by [[Feodor Chaliapin]], and has been a favourite concert piece of bass singers ever since. [[Bill Finegan]]'s jazz arrangement for the [[Glenn Miller]] band took the song to #1 in the US charts in 1941.  Russian composer [[Alexander Glazunov]] based one of the themes of his symphonic poem \"Stenka Razin\" on the song.  Spanish composer [[Manuel De Falla]] wrote an arrangement of the song, which was published under the name ''Canto de los remeros del Volga (del cancionero musical ruso)'' in 1922.<ref name=hess>Hess, Carol A. ''Sacred Passions: The Life and Music of Manuel de Falla'', Oxford University Press, 2005, p. 134. {{ISBN|0-19-514561-5}}.</ref> He did so at the behest of diplomat [[Ricardo Baeza (diplomat)|Ricardo Baeza]], who was working with the [[League of Nations]] to provide financial relief for the more than two million Russian refugees who had been displaced and imprisoned during [[World War I]].<ref name=hess /> All proceeds from the song's publication were donated to this effort.<ref name=hess /> [[Igor Stravinsky]] made an arrangement for orchestra.\n\n== First publications and recordings ==\nA version of the song was recorded by [[Mily Balakirev]] (a Russian composer) from Nikolay Aleynikov in [[Nizhny Novgorod]] in 1860 or 1861. Already in 1866, the musician published it in his book ''A collection of Russian folk songs'' by {{nowrap|M. Balakirev}} ({{lang-ru|\t\n\u00ab\u0421\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a\u044a \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445\u044a \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0445\u044a \u043f\u0463\u0441\u0435\u043d\u044a\u00bb}}; 1866), with his own arrangement.<ref name=\"\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u04411962\">{{cite book|author=\u0415. \u0412. \u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u0441|language=ru|title=\"\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c\": \"\u0414\u0443\u0431\u0438\u043d\u0443\u0448\u043a\u0430\" : \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0435\u0441\u0435\u043d|url=https://books.google.com/books?redir_esc=y&id=S0wIAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%D0%BA%D0%B5%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%D0%B0%D0%BD%D0%B0|year=1962|publisher=\u0421\u043e\u0432. \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043e\u0437\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|language=ru|title=\u0417\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0418\u043c\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0431\u0449\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0463\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0456\u044e \u044d\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444\u0456\u0438|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gd45AQAAMAAJ&q=%22%D0%A1%D0%B1%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D1%8A+%D1%80%D1%83%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BD%D1%8B%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BF%D1%A3%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8A%22+1866&dq=%22%D0%A1%D0%B1%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D1%8A+%D1%80%D1%83%D1%81%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BD%D0%B0%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4%D0%BD%D1%8B%D1%85%D1%8A+%D0%BF%D1%A3%D1%81%D0%B5%D0%BD%D1%8A%22+1866&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi_sZLEoJ_aAhUMCZoKHQ0EBtkQ6AEIKzAB}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title = \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u0438|language=ru|author=\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u0441, \u0415. \u0412.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&id=Qj0JAQAAMAAJ&dq=%D0%B1%D0%B0%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%BA%D0%B8%D1%80%D0%B5%D0%B2+%D0%B4%D1%83%D0%B1%D0%B8%D0%BD%D1%83%D1%88%D0%BA%D0%B0+%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B6%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%B9+%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B3%D0%BE%D1%80%D0%BE%D0%B4&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=%D0%90%D0%BB%D0%B5%D0%B9%D0%BD%D0%B8%D0%BA%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B0}}</ref>\n\nProbably, the first released version of the song was recorded in Russia in 1900 by Alexander Makarov-Yunev ({{lang-ru|{{nowrap|\u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432-\u042e\u043d\u0435\u0432}}}}) on [[Gramophone Company|Gramophone]] (#22086).<ref>{{cite book|author1=\u0413\u0440\u044e\u043d\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u041f. \u041d.|author2=\u042f\u043d\u0438\u043d \u0412. \u041b.|author2-link=Valentin Yanin|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0437\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 \u0432 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438. \u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433 \u0432\u043e\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0435\u0439 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0434\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0438 \"\u0413\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u043e\u0444\u043e\u043d\"|location=\u041c.|language=ru|publisher=\u042f\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0430\u0432\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b|pages=235|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qr1GAAAAMAAJ&q=22086+%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22&dq=22086+%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjVgujywZ7aAhXJECwKHcDeA38Q6AEIJDAA}}</ref>\n\n== Lyrics ==\n{| cellpadding=6\n! Russian\n! Transliteration\n! (Poetic) English translation\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n|\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0451\u0437\u0443,\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u043a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0443!\n:\u0410\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:A\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u043a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0443.\n\n:\u0420\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u044c\u0451\u043c \u043c\u044b \u043a\u0443\u0434\u0440\u044f\u0432\u0443.\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n\n:\u041c\u044b \u043f\u043e \u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0443 \u0438\u0434\u0451\u043c,\n:\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0451\u043c.\n:\u0410\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:A\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0451\u043c.\n\n:\u042d\u0439, \u044d\u0439, \u0442\u044f\u043d\u0438 \u043a\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442 \u0441\u0438\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0439!\n:\u041f\u0435\u0441\u043d\u044e \u0441\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u0448\u043a\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0451\u043c.\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n\n:\u042d\u0445 \u0442\u044b, \u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0430, \u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c-\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0430,\n:\u0428\u0438\u0440\u043e\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0433\u043b\u0443\u0431\u043e\u043a\u0430,\n:\u0410\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:A\u0439-\u0434\u0430, \u0434\u0430 \u0430\u0439-\u0434\u0430,\n:\u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0430, \u0412\u043e\u043b\u0433\u0430, \u043c\u0430\u0442\u044c-\u0440\u0435\u043a\u0430\n\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u0415\u0449\u0451 \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0438\u043a, \u0435\u0449\u0451 \u0434\u0430 \u0440\u0430\u0437!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n:\u042d\u0439, \u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!\n|\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n\n:Razovyom my byeryozu,\n:Razovyom my kudryavu!\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Razovyom my kudryavu.\n\n:Razovyom my kudryavu.\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n\n:My po byeryezhku idyom,\n:Pyesnyu solnyshku poyom.\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Pyesnyu solnyshku poyom.\n\n:Ey, Ey, tyani kanat silney!\n:Pyesnyu solnyshku poyom.\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n\n:Ekh, ty, Volga, mat'-reka,\n:Shiroka i gluboka,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Ai-da, da ai-da,\n:Volga, Volga, mat'-reka\n\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Yeshcho razik, yeshcho da raz!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n:Ey, ukhnyem!\n|\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n\n:Now we fell the stout birch tree,\n:Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n\n:Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n\n:As we walk along the shore,\n:To the sun we sing our song.\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:To the sun we sing our song.\n\n:Hey, hey, let's heave a-long the way\n:To the sun we sing our song\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n\n:Oh, you, Volga, mother river,\n:Mighty stream so deep and wide.\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Ay-da, da, ay-da!\n:Volga, Volga, mother river.\n\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Once more, once again, still once more\n:Yo, heave ho!\n:Yo, heave ho!\n|}\n\nThe English lyrics above fit the melody.  A more accurate translation of some lines are:\n{| cellpadding=6\n! Poetic\n! Literal\n|- style=\"vertical-align:top; white-space:nowrap;\"\n| Now we fell the stout birch tree,\n| We'll untwist the stout birch tree,\n|-\n| Now we pull hard: one, two, three.\n| We'll untwist the curly tree!\n|-\n| Hey, hey, let's heave a-long the way\n| Hey, hey, pull this way!\n|-\n| Mighty stream so deep and wide.\n| Wide and deep,\n|}\n\n== Notable recordings and arrangements ==\nThe song was arranged by [[Feodor Koenemann]] for [[Chaliapin]]. That Chaliapin's version became one of the most popular in Russia and has been released several times (e.g., in 1922, 1927, 1936).<ref name=\"\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u04411962\"/><ref>{{cite book|editor={{nowrap|\u0415. \u0410. \u0413\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0430}}|volume=II|pages=516, 517, 519|title=\u0428\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043f\u0438\u043d|publisher=\u0418\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e|location=\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430|year=1960|language=ru}}</ref>\n\nIn 1905, [[Alexander Glazunov]] created his piece ''Ey, ukhnem'' based on the Balakirev's tune.<ref name=\"\u0413\u0438\u043f\u043f\u0438\u0443\u04411962\"/><ref name=\"\u0412\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043b\u043e\u04321950\">{{cite book|author=\u0412\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432, \u0412. \u0412.|title=\u0421\u0438\u043c\u0444\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u0442\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0447\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0410.\u041a. \u0413\u043b\u0430\u0437\u0443\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3cguAAAAIAAJ&q=%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22+%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B7%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2+1905&dq=%22%D1%8D%D0%B9,+%D1%83%D1%85%D0%BD%D0%B5%D0%BC%22+%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B0%D0%B7%D1%83%D0%BD%D0%BE%D0%B2+1905&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiZsb_i-6HaAhXOZpoKHdyuBQw4HhDoAQhDMAc|year=1950|language=ru|publisher=\u0413\u043e\u0441. \u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0434-\u0432\u043e}}</ref>\n\nCzech composer [[V\u00edt\u011bzslav Nov\u00e1k]] utilizes the main motif from ''Song of the Volga Boatmen''  in his ''M\u00e1jov\u00e1 symfonie'' (''May Symphony'', Op.&nbsp;73, 1943), for soloists, mixed chorus, and orchestra.\n\nA translated vocal version was sung by [[Paul Robeson]].\n\nThe [[Boston Pops Orchestra]] conducted by [[Arthur Fiedler]] recorded the Glazunov arrangement of the tune in New York City on June 30, 1937.\n\nThe song, or at least the tune, was popularized in the mid-20th Century through an instrumental jazz version played by the [[Glenn Miller Band]].<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LJRts1kwzKc YouTube: The Song of the Volga Boatmen].</ref> Glenn Miller released the song as an RCA Bluebird 78 single, B-11029-A, in 1941 in a swing jazz arrangement by Bill Finegan which reached no. 1 on the ''Billboard'' pop singles chart in a 10-week chart run.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoffmann|first1=Frank|title=Chronology of American Popular Music, 1900-2000|date=May 23, 2016|publisher=Routledge|location=London; New York|isbn=978-0-415-97715-9|page=93|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hAI3DAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2016}}</ref>  Not in copyright, the song was not subject to the 1941 [[ASCAP boycott]], allowing for more radio play that year.<ref name=pc2b>{{Pop Chronicles 40s|2|B |url=https://digital.library.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metadc1633220/m1/#track/2}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 [[Leonid Kharitonov (singer)|Leonid Kharitonov]] with the Russian [[Alexandrov Ensemble|Red Army Choir]] released a recording.\n\nThe Swedish jazz pianist [[Jan Johansson (jazz musician)|Jan Johansson]] arranged an instrumental version for jazz trio (Pr\u00e5mdragarnas s\u00e5ng vid Volga) on his album \"Jazz P\u00e5 Ryska\"(1967).<ref>http://www.janjohansson.org/jpr.html</ref>\n\n== Modern popular culture ==\n{{refimprove section|date=March 2018}}\n[[File:Song of Volga Boatmen Glenn Miller 11029.jpg|thumb|1941 recording by Glenn Miller, RCA Bluebird, B-11029-A.]]\nThe memorable melody of ''The Song of the Volga Boatmen'' has led to its common usage in many musical situations, particularly as background music, often with the theme of unremitting toil (or, alternatively, devotion to duty). Some uses, particularly those portending doom or despair, employ only the iconic four-note beginning; others go so far as to add new, often wryly humorous, lyrics, such as the \"Birthday Dirge\".<ref>[http://www.faqs.org/faqs/music/birthday-dirge-faq/ The Birthday Dirge].</ref>  Some usages only acknowledge the tune's Russian heritage; very few use the original lyrics (for instance its use as the introductory theme of the Soviet boxer, [[Soda Popinski]], in ''[[Mike Tyson's Punch-Out!!]]'').\n\nInstances include:\n* The cartoon ''[[Goofy Gymnastics]]'' (1949)\n* [[Dickie Goodman]] in his 1959 novelty hit \"Russian Bandstand.\"\n* At 2:55 minutes in the song \"[[The Stroke]]\" by [[Billy Squier]].\n* In ''[[A Troll in Central Park]]'', a minor character sings \"I'm a bad troll, a very bad troll!\" to the tune.\n* The [[Fremantle Football Club]] of the [[Australian Football League]] based their inaugural club song on the tune, used between 1995 and 2011.\n* The Gainesville, Florida rock band [[The Vulgar Boatmen]] were named as a play on the original term.\n* [[Peter Schickele]] (writing as ''P D Q Bach'') used the tune for the subject of a [[fugue]] called \"Fuga Vulgaris\" in [[List of works by P. D. Q. Bach|Toot Suite for Calliope four hands]].\n* On the ''[[The Simpsons|Simpsons]]'' episode \"[[The Springfield Files]]\", when Homer takes the [[breathalyzer]] test, he reaches level \"[[Boris Yeltsin]]\", which then plays the song's tune.\n* On two episodes of ''[[SpongeBob SquarePants]]'': in \"Sandy, SpongeBob, and the Worm\", the song can be heard as Patrick and the townspeople push the city of Bikini Bottom; in \"Employee of the Month\", the song is heard as SpongeBob and Squidward crawl to the Krusty Krab \n* In the 2001 film ''[[Shrek]]'', the tune of the song is hummed by the dwarves as they are being led away in [[chain]]s. \n* The tune is used in 'Shirley Whirley' episode of ''[[Shaun the Sheep]]'' cartoon.\n* A piece by [[Gramatik]] (Denis Jasarevic), 'The Swing of Justice' (2014) reuses the Glenn Miller piece.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://pro.beatport.com/track/the-swing-of-justice-original-mix/5125911|title = Gramatik - The Swing Of Justice|date = |accessdate = 2015-05-14|website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* The song was used in the film ''[[Lord of War]]'' when Yuri is in [[Ukraine]] purchasing Soviet military hardware from his uncle after the [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union|breakup of the USSR]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Niccol|first=Andrew|title=Lord of War|date=2005-09-16|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0399295/soundtrack|accessdate=2016-05-28}}</ref>\n* The 1944 [[Warner Bros.]] cartoon ''[[Russian Rhapsody (film)|Russian Rhapsody]]'' features [[gremlin]]s dismantling [[Adolf Hitler]]'s [[airplane]].  They sing \"We are gremlins from the [[Kremlin]]\" to the tune of the song.\n* On the ''[[Gilligan's Island]]'' episode \"Goodbye, Old Paint\", a Russian artist ([[Harold J. Stone]]) sings the song while painting, occasionally making up his own lyrics.\n* The song was featured in the film  Tovarich (1937).\n\n* The theme of the Russian civilization in the series ''[[Civilization (series)|Civilization]]'', including the [[Sid Meier's Civilization|original game]] and its sequels ''[[Civilization II]]'' and ''[[Civilization IV]]''.\n* In [[Team Fortress 2]], the character Heavy can be heard singing the song at times.<ref>http://www.tf2sounds.com/1793#q%3Dsing</ref><ref>http://www.tf2sounds.com/475#q%3Dsing</ref>\n* The melody of the song is featured in [[Tetris: Axis]] for [[Nintendo 3DS]].\n* A rendition of the song is played in [[Pipe Mania]] for [[NES]] whenever a level is failed, or the game is over.\n* Parts of the song are used in the Malinovka map theme of [[World of Tanks]].\n* The video game [[Punch-Out!! (Wii)]] features the song in Russian character Soda Popinski's introductory cutscenes. It is also used to introduce him in the earlier [[Punch-Out!! (NES)|Nintendo Entertainment System version]].\n* The Fremantle Dockers (An Australian Rules Football club) used to base the official club song off of The Volga Boatmen until sections were removed.\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== See also ==\n{{Commons|File:\u042d\u0439,_\u0443\u0445\u043d\u0435\u043c!_-_\u0424\u0451\u0434\u043e\u0440_\u0428\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043f\u0438\u043d.ogg|The Song of the Volga Boatmen}}\n* [[List of number-one singles of 1941 (U.S.)]]\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SRe1dsXs6_s YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen]: Performed by Kovcheg Aca Pella; Five males, including two basso profundo.\n* {{IMSLP2|work=Song of the Volga Boatmen (Balakirev, Mily)|cname=Song of the Volga Boatmen}}.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8WD0WVL-HjE&feature=channel_page YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 sung in the tradition of [[Feodor Chaliapin|Chaliapin]] by [[Leonid Kharitonov (singer)|Leonid Kharitonov]] with the [[Alexandrov Ensemble]], 1965.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KfsWoNpHg2s YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 [[Paul Robeson]].\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gfigZBtAIjs YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 [[Glenn Miller]] and his orchestra.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LMbuUUk_3f4 YouTube: Song of the Volga Boatmen] \u2014 translated Chinese version performed by the Male Choir of the People's Armed Police.\n\n{{Glenn Miller}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Song of the Volga Boatmen, The}}\n[[Category:Russian folk songs]]\n[[Category:Sea shanties]]\n[[Category:Songs about rivers]]\n[[Category:Songs about boats]]\n[[Category:Year of song unknown]]\n[[Category:Feodor Chaliapin songs]]\n[[Category:Songs about Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Petrandreev13", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eModern popular culture", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Song_of_the_Volga_Boatmen"}
